1
00:02:02,583 --> 00:02:06,019
Containment breach!
We've had a major containment breach!

2
00:02:07,303 --> 00:02:08,782
Oh, my God.

3
00:02:08,863 --> 00:02:10,933
The security system
appears to be malfunctioning!

4
00:02:11,023 --> 00:02:14,095
Seal the base, Campion!
lf the main gate's still open, shut it!

5
00:02:14,183 --> 00:02:15,218
Yes, sir.

6
00:02:15,303 --> 00:02:17,339
People are dying like flies down here!

7
00:02:17,423 --> 00:02:19,414
Use the manual gate override, Campion!

8
00:02:19,503 --> 00:02:21,175
Do it now, do it now!

9
00:02:21,263 --> 00:02:22,662
Sally. Baby Lavon.

10
00:02:22,743 --> 00:02:24,813
Campion! This is a Code Red!

11
00:02:24,903 --> 00:02:26,575
We've lost one of the bugs!

12
00:02:26,663 --> 00:02:29,018
Repeat, we have lost one of the bugs!

13
00:02:29,103 --> 00:02:30,900
You have to close the gate!

14
00:02:32,663 --> 00:02:34,813
Sally!

15
00:02:35,863 --> 00:02:37,182
Charlie?

16
00:02:37,303 --> 00:02:39,180
-We gotta get out of here.
-What's going on?

17
00:02:39,263 --> 00:02:41,060
You know what.
Get the baby stuff, let's go!

18
00:02:41,143 --> 00:02:42,496
-Oh, my God!
-Come on! Let's go!

19
00:02:42,583 --> 00:02:44,301
-l'm coming!
-Let's go! Come on!

20
00:02:50,663 --> 00:02:52,301
Give me the baby!

21
00:02:53,743 --> 00:02:55,461
All right, let's go.

22
00:03:13,703 --> 00:03:14,897
Slow down, Charlie.

23
00:03:18,623 --> 00:03:20,375
Charlie, slow down!

24
00:03:24,383 --> 00:03:26,499
Charlie, you'll get us all killed!

25
00:03:35,223 --> 00:03:36,338
Sorry, baby.

26
00:05:12,903 --> 00:05:14,814
Blackout!

27
00:05:17,663 --> 00:05:22,214
And now, here is the host ofBlackout,
Bob Goen.

28
00:07:04,143 --> 00:07:06,054
Coming up next,
we got Kathi Kamen Goldmark...

29
00:07:06,143 --> 00:07:08,452
America 's new country sweetheart.

30
00:07:08,543 --> 00:07:10,056
Sure wish she was my sweetheart.

31
00:07:10,143 --> 00:07:12,099
Why don't you listen to me, old man?

32
00:07:12,183 --> 00:07:15,061
Been listening to you
more than 20 years now, ain't l?

33
00:07:15,143 --> 00:07:17,611
All that wisdom and l ain't rich yet.

34
00:07:18,823 --> 00:07:21,496
Yeah, well, if you learned
some simple economics.

35
00:07:22,903 --> 00:07:25,701
Old man Vic thinks simple economics...

36
00:07:26,663 --> 00:07:29,018
is some new breed of lrishman.

37
00:07:29,103 --> 00:07:30,616
Ain't you ignorant!

38
00:07:30,703 --> 00:07:33,012
Licking the glue off the back
of them food stamps...

39
00:07:33,103 --> 00:07:34,980
has finally done something to your brain.

40
00:07:35,063 --> 00:07:37,657
Well, l got to feed your daughter, don't l?

41
00:07:46,903 --> 00:07:48,416
Shut off the pumps.

42
00:08:15,863 --> 00:08:17,342
Look at him, Stu.

43
00:08:18,183 --> 00:08:21,653
You don't think he did that to his face
falling out of the car, do you?

44
00:08:21,743 --> 00:08:23,017
l doubt it.

45
00:08:28,743 --> 00:08:31,098
Just take it easy now. Calm down.

46
00:08:32,503 --> 00:08:36,018
Hap! Phone rescue services
in Braintree now.

47
00:08:36,103 --> 00:08:37,297
Hurry up! Go on!

48
00:08:39,263 --> 00:08:42,380
Just take it easy, friend.
lt's gonna be all right.

49
00:08:42,463 --> 00:08:44,931
Just lie still now. lt's all right.

50
00:08:49,823 --> 00:08:51,734
lt's gonna be all right.

51
00:08:58,143 --> 00:09:00,099
Ambulance will be here in 10 minutes.

52
00:09:00,183 --> 00:09:02,981
My wife and my baby are sick.
They need help.

53
00:09:03,703 --> 00:09:06,342
Help my wife and my baby.
They're sick, they need help!

54
00:09:06,423 --> 00:09:09,779
Okay, mister, they're fine.
You just want to sit right there.

55
00:09:10,143 --> 00:09:12,020
The ambulance is on its way.

56
00:09:12,623 --> 00:09:15,057
We didn't get out in time after all.

57
00:09:17,223 --> 00:09:20,738
You just try to rest yourself, okay?
Just take it easy now.

58
00:09:20,823 --> 00:09:23,895
Gate malfunctioned, otherwise
we would've died in the compound.

59
00:09:24,183 --> 00:09:25,536
Project Blue.

60
00:09:28,623 --> 00:09:31,581
Get his head over to the side, Stu.
He's gonna choke.

61
00:09:32,903 --> 00:09:34,302
Get your head down.

62
00:09:36,703 --> 00:09:37,977
Come on.

63
00:09:41,143 --> 00:09:42,212
Like l told you!

64
00:09:42,303 --> 00:09:44,692
l ain't got time to throw a line
over that dog's head!

65
00:09:44,783 --> 00:09:46,296
You mind me now!

66
00:09:46,943 --> 00:09:48,615
What's he got? You got any idea?

67
00:09:48,703 --> 00:09:51,376
Maybe it's food poisoning.
He's got California plates here.

68
00:09:51,463 --> 00:09:55,138
Maybe he got some bad chow
at a roadside stand or something.

69
00:09:55,663 --> 00:09:57,255
l hope you're right.

70
00:09:57,343 --> 00:10:00,062
l seen cholera back in '58
down near Nogales.

71
00:10:00,143 --> 00:10:01,735
This is what it looks like.

72
00:10:01,823 --> 00:10:05,133
Sally and the baby,
they were sick since Salt Lake City...

73
00:10:05,223 --> 00:10:07,657
but l felt fine until this morning.

74
00:10:09,103 --> 00:10:11,742
Are you sure Sally and my baby are okay?

75
00:10:13,263 --> 00:10:15,174
There was a man with us
some of the time.

76
00:10:15,263 --> 00:10:17,538
He was a dark man.

77
00:10:19,463 --> 00:10:21,693
l was looking through
the rear-view mirror...

78
00:10:21,783 --> 00:10:24,138
and l'd see him just sitting there
grinning at me.

79
00:10:25,383 --> 00:10:27,294
l thought l could outrun him...

80
00:10:30,063 --> 00:10:32,418
but you can't outrun the dark man.

81
00:11:10,463 --> 00:11:13,500
Not now. Hilly, put this on the wall.

82
00:11:29,703 --> 00:11:30,852
Come.

83
00:11:32,543 --> 00:11:33,692
General Starkey, sir!

84
00:11:33,783 --> 00:11:36,377
Close the door and drop the bull, Len.

85
00:11:36,463 --> 00:11:37,657
Yes, sir.

86
00:11:39,983 --> 00:11:42,133
lt killed them in a hurry down there.

87
00:11:42,223 --> 00:11:45,101
Telemetry suggests even the ones
who got their respirators on...

88
00:11:45,183 --> 00:11:47,014
died within 12 minutes.

89
00:11:47,103 --> 00:11:50,300
The rest of them were gone in five.
You believe that?

90
00:11:50,383 --> 00:11:52,294
-Do l have a choice?
-No.

91
00:11:52,663 --> 00:11:54,574
Apparently none of us do.

92
00:11:55,703 --> 00:11:58,695
lt's nothing but a souped-up version
of the flu.

93
00:11:59,343 --> 00:12:01,937
Herbert Denninger
of the National Disease Control Center...

94
00:12:02,023 --> 00:12:05,299
the Pentagon's bright boy of the week,
says once we find Campion...

95
00:12:05,383 --> 00:12:07,851
we'll know if it's actually
going to jump to the outside.

96
00:12:07,943 --> 00:12:11,094
He says it might mutate, but that won't
help the people that catch it.

97
00:12:11,183 --> 00:12:15,574
-Listen, l have what might be something--
-lt'll just take them longer to die, that's all.

98
00:12:15,663 --> 00:12:19,338
Most people are gonna think
they've got the plain old non-lethal flu...

99
00:12:19,423 --> 00:12:21,334
right up to the very end.

100
00:12:21,743 --> 00:12:24,541
And that's the biggest break
we've had so far.

101
00:12:24,623 --> 00:12:28,252
All because a gate malfunctioned,
and some glorified TV repairman...

102
00:12:28,343 --> 00:12:30,299
got his family and ran for the hills.

103
00:12:30,383 --> 00:12:32,180
l'd like to get him and string him up by--

104
00:12:32,263 --> 00:12:34,094
We found him. We located Campion.

105
00:12:34,183 --> 00:12:36,378
He crash-landed at a gas station
on the outskirts...

106
00:12:36,463 --> 00:12:39,023
of a one-stoplight town in east Texas.

107
00:12:39,103 --> 00:12:41,663
He made it halfway across the country?

108
00:12:41,743 --> 00:12:43,096
-How'd he do that?
-l don't know.

109
00:12:43,183 --> 00:12:46,539
The important thing is, right now,
we've got a shot at containing this.

110
00:12:46,623 --> 00:12:48,693
-ls he dead or alive?
-He's dead.

111
00:12:48,783 --> 00:12:51,297
Denninger says this stuff
has a communicability level...

112
00:12:51,383 --> 00:12:53,851
of over 99%.
Do you understand what that means?

113
00:12:53,943 --> 00:12:56,332
Any chance we had of containing it
went by the boards...

114
00:12:56,423 --> 00:12:58,732
when Campion bought
his first takeout hamburger.

115
00:13:00,103 --> 00:13:02,298
We can't think that way, Billy.

116
00:13:05,503 --> 00:13:08,097
Yeah, you're right. Of course you are.

117
00:13:08,503 --> 00:13:11,700
-What about the rest of his family?
-They're dead, sir.

118
00:13:13,343 --> 00:13:16,380
-Contact with townspeople was minimal.
-That doesn't matter.

119
00:13:16,463 --> 00:13:18,897
We gotta shut that town down,
lock it up...

120
00:13:18,983 --> 00:13:20,177
dig a moat around it.

121
00:13:20,263 --> 00:13:23,175
That operation's already
on the launching pad, sir.

122
00:13:23,303 --> 00:13:26,500
-What kind of coverage you come up with?
-Anthrax.

123
00:13:27,583 --> 00:13:28,777
New strain.

124
00:13:30,223 --> 00:13:33,454
Yeah, it's a new one, all right.
lt's real new.

125
00:13:34,223 --> 00:13:37,738
lt's very good at its job, too. Too good.

126
00:13:42,263 --> 00:13:45,733
-lt's bad, General, but it could be worse.
-How's that?

127
00:13:47,143 --> 00:13:49,293
What's the name of this town?

128
00:13:50,383 --> 00:13:51,577
Arnette.

129
00:13:52,303 --> 00:13:53,622
Arnette, Texas.

130
00:14:04,103 --> 00:14:05,252
Cold got you down?

131
00:14:05,343 --> 00:14:08,460
Chills, fever?
Sounds like you need a buddy!

132
00:14:08,543 --> 00:14:09,817
Flu Buddy!

133
00:14:10,143 --> 00:14:13,499
Fast-acting Flu Buddy,
available at pharmacies everywhere.

134
00:14:14,103 --> 00:14:15,377
Flu Buddy!

135
00:14:15,463 --> 00:14:18,933
And now let's get back
to the Lone Star matinee movie.

136
00:14:23,903 --> 00:14:27,782
State Patrol, Hap.
Looks like your cousin Joe-Bob.

137
00:14:29,623 --> 00:14:32,581
Hey, Joe-Bob.
Want me to fill her up for you?

138
00:14:33,543 --> 00:14:35,977
No, sir, l come by on other business.

139
00:14:36,383 --> 00:14:39,614
Was that old geezer here last night
when that guy took out your pumps?

140
00:14:39,703 --> 00:14:41,819
Vic? He's here just about every night.

141
00:14:41,903 --> 00:14:44,781
-Maybe he ought to hear this, too.
-Hear what?

142
00:14:45,543 --> 00:14:48,011
There's strangers
crawling all over Braintree.

143
00:14:48,103 --> 00:14:50,139
Supposed to be U.S. Health Service guys...

144
00:14:50,223 --> 00:14:54,182
but they came in a C-5A transport plane,
and they look like regular Army to me.

145
00:14:54,263 --> 00:14:56,493
Then there's been
three more big transport planes...

146
00:14:56,583 --> 00:14:59,256
land over Starland in Arkansas since noon.

147
00:14:59,543 --> 00:15:01,659
lt was cholera. l knew it was.

148
00:15:02,023 --> 00:15:03,900
l don't know nothing about that.

149
00:15:03,983 --> 00:15:05,416
l'll tell you one thing, though.

150
00:15:05,503 --> 00:15:07,619
lf the Feds are thinking about
a quarantine...

151
00:15:07,703 --> 00:15:11,616
then you might have a little bit more
to worry about than cholera.

152
00:15:11,863 --> 00:15:14,900
l just thought you ought to know
what's stirring in the weeds, Hap.

153
00:15:14,983 --> 00:15:17,372
lf any of them other boys
from last night come by...

154
00:15:17,463 --> 00:15:21,012
you ought to pass the word along to them.
Just don't mention my name.

155
00:15:21,183 --> 00:15:24,778
You ought take care of that, old-timer.
Them summer colds are the worst.

156
00:15:34,303 --> 00:15:36,021
What if it ain't a cold?

157
00:15:36,183 --> 00:15:39,095
What if l got whatever he had?
That guy last night?

158
00:15:39,183 --> 00:15:42,175
lt's probably just the sniffles, that's all.

159
00:15:48,383 --> 00:15:51,455
Maybe l ought to close up the station
for the rest of the day.

160
00:15:51,543 --> 00:15:53,420
Call the others
and see how they're feeling.

161
00:15:53,503 --> 00:15:55,300
Might not be a bad idea.

162
00:16:07,383 --> 00:16:08,498
Dang!

163
00:16:14,943 --> 00:16:17,138
This is Unit 16 to base.

164
00:16:17,303 --> 00:16:20,898
l'm seeing a lot of Army traffic
on State 17...

165
00:16:20,983 --> 00:16:23,099
westbound in the direction of Arnette.

166
00:16:23,383 --> 00:16:25,499
You heard anything about that? Bye.

167
00:16:25,583 --> 00:16:28,302
Please advise if you've been
anywhere near Arnette today. Bye.

168
00:16:33,343 --> 00:16:34,492
Negative, base.

169
00:16:34,583 --> 00:16:37,575
l've been over
by the Arkansas state line all day.

170
00:16:37,983 --> 00:16:39,132
Well, that's fine then.

171
00:16:39,223 --> 00:16:41,293
Suggest you let the Army
mind their business...

172
00:16:41,383 --> 00:16:43,613
and you mind yours, Unit 16. Bye.

173
00:16:44,103 --> 00:16:46,776
You don't have to be so grouchy
about it, Cynthia !

174
00:16:47,543 --> 00:16:49,374
Unit 16, over and out.

175
00:17:03,183 --> 00:17:04,741
All right, let's move it out.

176
00:17:13,863 --> 00:17:15,774
Come on, toss it!

177
00:17:19,983 --> 00:17:21,735
Shoot it!

178
00:17:45,783 --> 00:17:47,421
Hold it right there, now!

179
00:18:01,703 --> 00:18:03,341
l can't leave my store.

180
00:18:03,423 --> 00:18:05,618
Hey, what right have you got
to push me around?

181
00:18:10,463 --> 00:18:12,454
Stuart Richard Redman, sir.

182
00:18:12,983 --> 00:18:14,780
He was at the station.

183
00:18:25,823 --> 00:18:27,415
Sounds like you're having a busy day.

184
00:18:27,503 --> 00:18:30,700
Dr. Herbert Denninger, Mr. Redman.
Will you come with us?

185
00:18:32,303 --> 00:18:35,022
You want to get your hand
off my arm, hoss?

186
00:18:35,463 --> 00:18:37,579
He was in direct contact with Campion.

187
00:18:37,663 --> 00:18:40,814
-Put him in the truck. lf he resists....
-l ain't gonna resist.

188
00:18:42,783 --> 00:18:44,660
Country don't mean dumb.

189
00:18:51,983 --> 00:18:54,213
l ain't going! l ain't!

190
00:18:54,943 --> 00:18:56,774
Get your hands off her!

191
00:18:57,983 --> 00:19:01,498
Stay where you are, Mr. Redman.
That's none of your affair.

192
00:19:03,143 --> 00:19:05,657
Stu, what's happening?

193
00:19:07,863 --> 00:19:10,138
They want to take us to Vermont!

194
00:19:10,583 --> 00:19:14,098
Mr. Redman, l insist you get into the truck
right now, or....

195
00:19:14,863 --> 00:19:18,139
Or what? You'll shoot me?

196
00:19:18,783 --> 00:19:20,933
That don't scare me much, hoss.

197
00:19:21,063 --> 00:19:24,180
lf we got what that guy Campion had,
we're dead already.

198
00:19:25,143 --> 00:19:26,337
Right?

199
00:19:53,343 --> 00:19:56,653
Well, our flying time today will be
three hours and forty minutes...

200
00:19:56,743 --> 00:19:59,257
and Uncle Sam is buying all the drinks.

201
00:19:59,383 --> 00:20:01,499
What the hell's wrong with us?

202
00:20:01,703 --> 00:20:03,694
-ls it cholera?
-Absolutely not.

203
00:20:03,783 --> 00:20:05,421
You'll be getting all the details....

204
00:20:05,503 --> 00:20:06,572
When?

205
00:20:06,863 --> 00:20:08,933
Shortly after you land.

206
00:20:17,743 --> 00:20:21,053
l ain't been this scared
since the Mekong Delta in '69.

207
00:20:23,503 --> 00:20:26,381
No, that ain't true.
l never been this scared.

208
00:20:28,503 --> 00:20:31,415
lt's just the ones that was there
when Campion croaked, ain't it?

209
00:20:31,503 --> 00:20:34,495
Us, our families,
the people we been around since.

210
00:20:34,703 --> 00:20:36,375
Right now, yeah.

211
00:20:36,823 --> 00:20:38,415
What do you mean, right now?

212
00:20:38,503 --> 00:20:40,380
Okay, people, saddle up.

213
00:20:41,143 --> 00:20:45,022
Let's go!
You're on Uncle Sam's time now. Move it.

214
00:20:45,903 --> 00:20:47,382
Move them out!

215
00:20:52,703 --> 00:20:54,659
Arnette's been cancelled.

216
00:20:55,103 --> 00:20:57,059
-Serious?
-What do you think?

217
00:20:57,143 --> 00:20:58,542
l don't know.

218
00:21:01,183 --> 00:21:02,980
l think we're in big trouble.

219
00:21:06,063 --> 00:21:08,338
And now, by request from Bay Ridge...

220
00:21:08,423 --> 00:21:11,256
Larry Underwood
and Baby Can You Dig Your Man.

221
00:21:11,343 --> 00:21:12,935
Well, baby, can you?

222
00:22:16,783 --> 00:22:17,818
Ma !

223
00:22:33,943 --> 00:22:35,661
You look beautiful.

224
00:22:37,303 --> 00:22:39,294
Aren't you glad to see me?

225
00:22:39,703 --> 00:22:41,341
Should l be, Larry?

226
00:22:42,503 --> 00:22:46,416
Well, l can be happy for the both of us
if l have to be.

227
00:22:55,143 --> 00:22:58,613
Come on inside, Larry,
before the neighbors get an eyeful.

228
00:23:02,383 --> 00:23:05,056
So you know the record cracked
the top 50?

229
00:23:06,263 --> 00:23:09,699
-You heard it, right?
-Of course l have. You sound black.

230
00:23:10,943 --> 00:23:13,377
That brown sound sure do get around!

231
00:23:20,663 --> 00:23:21,732
Right.

232
00:23:22,423 --> 00:23:23,856
So l'm in L.A...

233
00:23:24,943 --> 00:23:27,013
and all of a sudden, everyone's my friend.

234
00:23:27,103 --> 00:23:29,219
And everyone's got a ''can't miss'' deal.

235
00:23:29,303 --> 00:23:31,658
So l had to get out of there
for a little while.

236
00:23:31,743 --> 00:23:33,574
Take a little time off.

237
00:23:36,743 --> 00:23:38,495
How's your back, Ma?

238
00:23:38,823 --> 00:23:41,178
Pains me some, but l got my pills.

239
00:23:44,863 --> 00:23:47,457
What kind of trouble are you in, Larry?

240
00:23:54,863 --> 00:23:57,377
Maybe l overspent my advance a little.

241
00:23:58,183 --> 00:24:01,493
l didn't know the record company
was gonna be so cheap.

242
00:24:03,063 --> 00:24:04,655
lt's no big deal...

243
00:24:07,343 --> 00:24:09,652
except l borrowed a little money.

244
00:24:09,743 --> 00:24:12,621
And not from any bank,
or you wouldn't be here, right?

245
00:24:19,183 --> 00:24:22,937
Are the leg-breakers any different
on the West Coast than they are here?

246
00:24:23,023 --> 00:24:26,652
Do they give you a Perrier and Valium
before they start hurting you?

247
00:24:26,743 --> 00:24:28,301
You're just like your father.

248
00:24:28,383 --> 00:24:30,738
-l'm not just like Pop!
-You sound pissed off.

249
00:24:30,823 --> 00:24:33,383
-l am pissed off, Ma !
-Good.

250
00:24:34,823 --> 00:24:38,941
lt's good to know that there's still
a real person in there someplace.

251
00:24:42,623 --> 00:24:45,695
How deep a hole are you in? And don't lie.

252
00:24:46,463 --> 00:24:48,101
l've seen your car.

253
00:24:49,263 --> 00:24:50,696
About $40,000.

254
00:24:51,943 --> 00:24:53,217
Jesus wept.

255
00:25:02,783 --> 00:25:06,492
But the record's number 21 this week, Ma,
with a bullet.

256
00:25:08,303 --> 00:25:11,181
The album hasn't hit the Hot 100 yet,
but it will.

257
00:25:11,263 --> 00:25:13,015
$40,000 is nothing.

258
00:25:13,743 --> 00:25:15,142
Nothing.

259
00:25:15,623 --> 00:25:18,091
l'm not gonna let them make me
a one-hit wonder, either.

260
00:25:18,183 --> 00:25:22,142
Your son's here to stick around.
l'm going to be famous, Ma.

261
00:25:22,423 --> 00:25:25,256
Even better, l'm going to be rich.

262
00:25:32,703 --> 00:25:35,012
The bed's still in your old room.

263
00:25:35,343 --> 00:25:37,652
l'll make it up,
but then l have to go to work.

264
00:25:37,743 --> 00:25:40,701
-l'm gonna be late as it is.
-All right. Thanks.

265
00:25:43,743 --> 00:25:45,142
Thanks, Ma.

266
00:25:52,743 --> 00:25:54,495
Welcome home, Larry.

267
00:26:38,703 --> 00:26:41,058
This is interesting. Now watch this.

268
00:27:06,263 --> 00:27:08,015
lt's so damn quick.

269
00:27:09,743 --> 00:27:13,179
The only two left from the gas station
are Bruett and Redman, correct?

270
00:27:13,263 --> 00:27:15,857
Yes. Bruett's critical and sinking fast...

271
00:27:15,943 --> 00:27:18,821
which leaves only Redman,
who's not even sick.

272
00:27:21,903 --> 00:27:24,371
Now how in God's name is that possible?

273
00:27:24,463 --> 00:27:27,580
l don't know, but we're going to find out.

274
00:27:28,023 --> 00:27:30,776
We have to find out. And soon.

275
00:27:30,863 --> 00:27:32,501
We will.

276
00:28:00,463 --> 00:28:01,418
ln other news...

277
00:28:01,503 --> 00:28:04,381
U.S. Government health officials
claim there's nothing strange...

278
00:28:04,463 --> 00:28:07,500
in their decision to quarantine
a small east Texas town...

279
00:28:07,583 --> 00:28:10,097
where a new strain
of what's believed to be swine flu...

280
00:28:10,183 --> 00:28:12,413
has got half the population in bed...

281
00:28:12,503 --> 00:28:15,813
and the other half down with the sniffles.
At the Vermont Center....

282
00:28:15,903 --> 00:28:17,336
Hello, Mr. Goldsmith!

283
00:28:17,423 --> 00:28:19,653
-Hello, Harold!
-ls Fran around?

284
00:28:23,223 --> 00:28:25,418
She's in the kitchen, l think.

285
00:28:32,423 --> 00:28:34,220
-Hi, Fran.
-Hi, Harold.

286
00:28:34,903 --> 00:28:37,895
-Thanks, Daddy.
-Don't mention it, sweetheart.

287
00:28:40,023 --> 00:28:42,412
-l brought you something.
-You did?

288
00:28:44,783 --> 00:28:46,136
ls that you?

289
00:28:47,223 --> 00:28:50,021
Of course, Everleafis just
a small literary magazine.

290
00:28:50,103 --> 00:28:53,334
Small but prestigious.
And they only pay in contributors' copies.

291
00:28:53,423 --> 00:28:55,983
Look, Daddy, we know a published writer.

292
00:28:56,263 --> 00:28:58,174
How about that!

293
00:29:01,183 --> 00:29:04,493
My poem is called ''The Crushed Rose.''
l marked it for you.

294
00:29:05,663 --> 00:29:09,781
l actually sent in three,
but, of course, their space is very limited.

295
00:29:10,583 --> 00:29:13,893
Harold, l'm going to read this
just as soon as l get a chance. Thanks.

296
00:29:13,983 --> 00:29:16,292
ln the meantime, congratulations.

297
00:29:17,583 --> 00:29:18,857
Thank you.

298
00:29:19,023 --> 00:29:21,901
l had another reason for stopping by,
as well.

299
00:29:26,303 --> 00:29:28,373
l was wondering
if you would care to accompany me...

300
00:29:28,463 --> 00:29:30,818
to the Redwood Cinema this Friday
in Boothbay.

301
00:29:30,903 --> 00:29:32,575
They're having a Bergman festival.

302
00:29:32,663 --> 00:29:36,292
l've always found Cries and Whispers
to be especially moving.

303
00:29:36,583 --> 00:29:40,735
You see, Amy and l already decided to go
to an R.E.M. concert in Portland.

304
00:29:42,303 --> 00:29:43,452
Sorry.

305
00:29:44,743 --> 00:29:46,813
Well, maybe some other time.

306
00:29:51,743 --> 00:29:53,893
l'm sure you'll find somebody to go with.

307
00:29:53,983 --> 00:29:56,451
You know, maybe somebody
even your own age.

308
00:29:56,783 --> 00:29:58,739
l mean.... l didn't mean that.

309
00:30:00,103 --> 00:30:03,539
Hey, no, don't worry about it.
lt's okay. l understand, really.

310
00:30:03,743 --> 00:30:05,495
-l hope you enjoy the poem...
-l will--

311
00:30:05,583 --> 00:30:06,902
...and the rest of the magazine.

312
00:30:06,983 --> 00:30:09,497
Why don't you stay
and have some iced tea or something?

313
00:30:09,583 --> 00:30:12,336
No, thanks. l'm actually in sort of a hurry.

314
00:30:21,543 --> 00:30:24,103
l really handled that great, didn't l?

315
00:30:25,143 --> 00:30:28,977
Considering that Harold Lauder's had
a crush on you since he was 9 years old...

316
00:30:29,063 --> 00:30:31,054
yeah, l think you did okay.

317
00:30:32,223 --> 00:30:33,702
Let me see that.

318
00:30:37,743 --> 00:30:42,259
''l have stridden the fuming way
Of sun-hammered tracks

319
00:30:42,343 --> 00:30:44,811
''And savage hobo jungles''

320
00:30:44,903 --> 00:30:46,575
Stop!

321
00:30:52,343 --> 00:30:53,571
Frannie?

322
00:30:54,223 --> 00:30:56,498
-Are you okay?
-Yeah.

323
00:30:57,503 --> 00:30:59,971
l'm the object
of a young poet's unrequited love.

324
00:31:00,063 --> 00:31:01,655
What else could a girl want?

325
00:31:02,703 --> 00:31:05,934
You and Jess haven't had a fight?

326
00:31:06,423 --> 00:31:08,618
l haven't seen much of him this summer.

327
00:31:11,023 --> 00:31:14,299
Actually, Jess and l have decided
to spend some time apart.

328
00:31:16,583 --> 00:31:19,256
lt's like that, is it?

329
00:31:20,423 --> 00:31:22,061
Yeah, just like that.

330
00:31:23,543 --> 00:31:26,535
Come here. Give your old man a hug.

331
00:31:32,183 --> 00:31:35,334
-What about you? How are you doing?
-l'm fine.

332
00:31:36,863 --> 00:31:41,095
l woke up this morning
missing your mother, so l came out here.

333
00:31:43,143 --> 00:31:44,576
After seven years...

334
00:31:45,263 --> 00:31:48,141
there's a lot of places in the house
where she ain't...

335
00:31:48,223 --> 00:31:50,134
but this ain't one of them.

336
00:31:51,303 --> 00:31:55,501
Sometimes when l'm out here
yanking weeds, l can almost see her.

337
00:31:57,783 --> 00:31:59,262
l love you, Daddy.

338
00:32:00,223 --> 00:32:01,622
l love you, too.

339
00:32:03,303 --> 00:32:06,659
Although l've resigned myself
to losing you to Harold Lauder someday.

340
00:32:06,743 --> 00:32:07,778
No!

341
00:32:12,983 --> 00:32:14,211
You okay?

342
00:32:32,223 --> 00:32:34,498
And how are you today, Mr. Redman?

343
00:32:35,943 --> 00:32:37,934
We're just going to do a few routine tests.

344
00:32:38,023 --> 00:32:41,333
-lf l could have your arm....
-No, l won't be doing any more tests.

345
00:32:41,423 --> 00:32:43,379
lt's just your blood pressure.
Doctor's orders.

346
00:32:43,463 --> 00:32:47,012
No, l want to talk to a doctor.
l want to talk to a doctor in person.

347
00:32:47,103 --> 00:32:49,492
l'm sure that you'll be talking to a doctor
very soon.

348
00:32:49,583 --> 00:32:51,938
Yeah, l'm sure l will, too. No more tests!

349
00:32:52,463 --> 00:32:53,896
-l'm sick of it!
-Mr. Redman, if--

350
00:32:57,143 --> 00:32:59,862
l think you'd better get in there, don't you?

351
00:33:31,183 --> 00:33:35,415
Say, if it isn't the man with
the little clipboard and the armed escort.

352
00:33:38,823 --> 00:33:41,621
No, we don't shake hands here.
Just a precaution.

353
00:33:42,623 --> 00:33:43,851
A precaution.

354
00:33:45,783 --> 00:33:48,251
Patty Greer says you've given her
quite a bit of trouble.

355
00:33:48,343 --> 00:33:50,618
-She's quite upset.
-That makes two of us.

356
00:33:51,743 --> 00:33:54,735
Being hijacked by some government
sons of bitches in space suits...

357
00:33:54,823 --> 00:33:56,654
does that to me every time.

358
00:33:56,743 --> 00:33:59,052
lf you don't want to see me
rip a hole in that...

359
00:33:59,143 --> 00:34:02,579
before you can get out of here,
you better give me a little information.

360
00:34:02,663 --> 00:34:06,417
-You tell me why l'm not sick.
-Mr. Redman, l hardly think....

361
00:34:06,503 --> 00:34:08,892
-Talk to me, damn it!
-l'm sorry, but you....

362
00:34:12,023 --> 00:34:14,093
Mr. Redman, be reasonable.

363
00:34:14,383 --> 00:34:16,658
Just get out of here, you little weasel.

364
00:34:18,503 --> 00:34:20,892
You send me someone
who'll give me some answers.

365
00:34:20,983 --> 00:34:23,577
l don't think
you quite appreciate your position.

366
00:34:23,663 --> 00:34:25,381
You're wrong about that.

367
00:34:26,463 --> 00:34:27,532
l do.

368
00:34:28,583 --> 00:34:29,777
Go on. Get out.

369
00:35:04,543 --> 00:35:05,578
Here he comes.

370
00:35:06,023 --> 00:35:09,254
-We won't really hurt him, will we, Ray?
-Quiet down.

371
00:35:11,263 --> 00:35:12,378
Get him !

372
00:35:13,783 --> 00:35:15,853
What the hell are you waiting for?

373
00:35:18,863 --> 00:35:21,252
Next time l yell, friend,
you're gonna pay attention.

374
00:35:21,343 --> 00:35:22,662
l guarantee it.

375
00:35:23,263 --> 00:35:24,901
Hold him ! Hold the sucker!

376
00:35:33,143 --> 00:35:35,373
Hold him. l'm gonna mess him up.

377
00:35:39,503 --> 00:35:41,141
How come he don't say nothing?

378
00:35:42,543 --> 00:35:44,659
By the time l finish with him,
he'll be singing...

379
00:35:44,743 --> 00:35:46,222
The Battle Hymn of the Republic.

380
00:35:46,303 --> 00:35:49,534
Sucker almost ruined my favorite shirt.
l'm gonna mess him up.

381
00:35:50,303 --> 00:35:52,897
-Stop it, Ray! You're killing him !
-Ray, car!

382
00:35:54,423 --> 00:35:57,221
-No!
-Heads up, sucker!

383
00:36:59,263 --> 00:37:00,582
l can hear!

384
00:37:02,063 --> 00:37:03,576
l can talk!

385
00:37:21,503 --> 00:37:22,731
l can hear.

386
00:37:24,303 --> 00:37:25,452
l can talk.

387
00:37:26,623 --> 00:37:30,332
l know, Nick. Praise God.

388
00:37:32,103 --> 00:37:33,934
How did you know my name?

389
00:37:34,143 --> 00:37:36,373
Come to me in a dream, l reckon.

390
00:37:37,183 --> 00:37:38,536
ls this a dream?

391
00:37:40,303 --> 00:37:42,612
Mayhap it is, and mayhap it ain't.

392
00:37:46,503 --> 00:37:48,141
Who are you, ma'am?

393
00:37:49,503 --> 00:37:51,698
Abagail Freemantle.

394
00:37:52,383 --> 00:37:55,773
But folks around these parts
just call me Mother Abagail.

395
00:37:57,703 --> 00:38:02,174
l'm 106 years old
and l still make my own bread.

396
00:38:03,423 --> 00:38:07,416
l been living right here
in Hemingford Home, Nebraska, all my life.

397
00:38:09,543 --> 00:38:11,534
You come see me, Nick.

398
00:38:11,983 --> 00:38:14,543
You and all your friends.

399
00:38:15,183 --> 00:38:17,094
You got to hurry, though.

400
00:38:22,943 --> 00:38:24,740
There's a storm coming.

401
00:38:26,703 --> 00:38:28,022
His storm.

402
00:39:07,983 --> 00:39:11,259
Some people have even taken
to wearing protection on the streets.

403
00:39:11,343 --> 00:39:14,255
-Why are you wearing this mask, sir?
-l don't know. Just feel safer.

404
00:39:14,423 --> 00:39:15,492
Okay. Thank you.

405
00:39:15,583 --> 00:39:18,222
The folks at the
Atlanta Disease Control Center told me...

406
00:39:18,303 --> 00:39:21,500
that these masks wouldn't stop
'"a flu germ with a hangover. '"

407
00:39:21,583 --> 00:39:24,097
-Gin.
-So l guess we can thank our lucky stars...

408
00:39:24,183 --> 00:39:26,743
that this outbreak of superflu
is just another urban....

409
00:39:26,823 --> 00:39:29,053
l don't know about all those people
down in Texas...

410
00:39:29,143 --> 00:39:32,772
but you sure sound
like you got a dose of the flu, Johnny.

411
00:39:33,063 --> 00:39:35,623
-You better let me take a listen.
-Forget that.

412
00:39:36,383 --> 00:39:37,736
Come on.

413
00:39:38,023 --> 00:39:41,060
You know how hot it makes me
when you take your shirt off.

414
00:39:51,623 --> 00:39:56,014
When l was a boy, we caught ourselves
a mountain lion back up in the hills.

415
00:39:56,143 --> 00:39:58,703
We shot it and dragged it back to town.

416
00:39:59,583 --> 00:40:01,858
What was left of that critter
when we got home...

417
00:40:01,943 --> 00:40:04,298
was the sorriest-looking sight
l've ever seen.

418
00:40:05,303 --> 00:40:06,975
You're the second sorriest, boy.

419
00:40:08,143 --> 00:40:12,739
l'm gonna get somebody to take
his shirt off before l go home tonight.

420
00:40:15,143 --> 00:40:17,213
lt's okay, son. l'm a doctor.

421
00:40:19,743 --> 00:40:22,780
l'm also the guy
who damn near ran you over.

422
00:40:23,463 --> 00:40:25,419
You got a name, babalugah?

423
00:40:32,343 --> 00:40:33,776
What the hell?

424
00:40:40,543 --> 00:40:42,693
lt means that he's deaf and dumb.

425
00:40:45,503 --> 00:40:46,777
That hurt?

426
00:40:49,463 --> 00:40:50,612
lf you're deaf and dumb...

427
00:40:50,703 --> 00:40:54,537
how the hell am l gonna to find out
what happened to you tonight?

428
00:41:14,863 --> 00:41:16,979
Can you read lips, babalugah?

429
00:41:18,383 --> 00:41:20,374
Thank God for small favors.

430
00:41:20,783 --> 00:41:22,262
Tell me this...

431
00:41:22,423 --> 00:41:26,336
would you know the three boys
that jobbed you if you seen them again?

432
00:41:28,183 --> 00:41:29,218
What?

433
00:41:32,183 --> 00:41:34,333
One of them had a ring like that?

434
00:41:35,303 --> 00:41:36,372
Man!

435
00:41:36,463 --> 00:41:39,023
That's a fraternity ring, my silent friend.

436
00:41:39,103 --> 00:41:42,300
And the only two people around here
who have them...

437
00:41:42,383 --> 00:41:46,092
are our esteemed sheriff and Ray Booth,
our town bad boy.

438
00:41:47,383 --> 00:41:50,261
The Sheriff here married Ray's baby sister.

439
00:41:51,623 --> 00:41:53,614
Janey's gonna just love this.

440
00:41:58,663 --> 00:42:00,142
Welcome to Shoyo, Mr. Andros.

441
00:42:00,423 --> 00:42:03,574
lt's a veritable hotbed
of Southern hospitality.

442
00:42:03,663 --> 00:42:05,096
Get away from me.

443
00:42:20,823 --> 00:42:23,257
l don't know how many different ways
l can say this.

444
00:42:23,343 --> 00:42:26,813
This so-called superflu does not exist.

445
00:42:28,583 --> 00:42:31,302
Then what is it?
Why is everybody talking about it?

446
00:42:31,383 --> 00:42:33,419
l don't know
why everybody's talking about it...

447
00:42:33,503 --> 00:42:34,936
or where the rumors are coming from.

448
00:42:35,023 --> 00:42:37,253
lt must be a figment
of the press's imagination.

449
00:42:37,343 --> 00:42:39,254
l don't know why l'm here
answering questions.

450
00:42:39,343 --> 00:42:42,699
l don't have the answers
because there's no such thing....

451
00:42:44,823 --> 00:42:47,496
Good afternoon, Mr. Redman.
My name is Deitz.

452
00:42:48,063 --> 00:42:50,213
l'd like you to meet a friend of mine.

453
00:42:54,623 --> 00:42:56,932
Meet Geraldo.

454
00:42:58,063 --> 00:42:59,018
Geraldo?

455
00:43:00,223 --> 00:43:03,056
Now, the virus
your fellow townspeople contracted...

456
00:43:03,143 --> 00:43:07,341
passes easily from human to guinea pig
and vice versa, presumably.

457
00:43:07,663 --> 00:43:12,418
But Geraldo has been breathing your air
via convector for the last three days...

458
00:43:13,463 --> 00:43:17,581
and Geraldo is fine and frisky, as you see.

459
00:43:19,503 --> 00:43:22,381
l'd call that rather comforting,
wouldn't you?

460
00:43:22,903 --> 00:43:27,135
-l see you're not taking any chances.
-That's not in my contract.

461
00:43:27,503 --> 00:43:28,982
However, it does appear...

462
00:43:29,063 --> 00:43:32,373
that there's absolutely nothing
wrong with you, Mr. Redman...

463
00:43:32,503 --> 00:43:34,573
or may l call you Stu?

464
00:43:35,703 --> 00:43:37,534
Just don't call me Geraldo.

465
00:43:38,623 --> 00:43:39,897
l like that.

466
00:43:41,303 --> 00:43:42,975
Now look here, Stu...

467
00:43:43,543 --> 00:43:47,775
let's try to get through this as painlessly
as possible, what do you say?

468
00:43:50,303 --> 00:43:53,181
Okay, here's number one:

469
00:43:54,303 --> 00:43:58,615
The testing schedule we began
earlier this week is going to resume...

470
00:43:58,863 --> 00:44:02,094
with your cooperation or without it.

471
00:44:02,743 --> 00:44:06,258
We got a hell of a mess on our hands here,
thanks to that imbecile Campion.

472
00:44:06,343 --> 00:44:09,062
So l don't want you to get the idea
you're a volunteer.

473
00:44:09,143 --> 00:44:10,815
You've been drafted.

474
00:44:16,343 --> 00:44:19,335
-What about the folks l came in with?
-From Arnette?

475
00:44:19,943 --> 00:44:22,377
All dead. Which is why we can't afford to--

476
00:44:23,863 --> 00:44:27,139
What did you do? What did you people do?

477
00:44:27,223 --> 00:44:29,373
Stu, please.

478
00:44:32,383 --> 00:44:34,419
No! Stand clear!

479
00:44:52,823 --> 00:44:54,779
All right, now you listen up...

480
00:44:56,063 --> 00:44:59,260
l'm not responsible for you being here...

481
00:44:59,663 --> 00:45:02,302
or for the dead people in your hometown.

482
00:45:02,503 --> 00:45:06,621
Neither is Denninger, or the nurses
who come in to take your blood pressure.

483
00:45:06,703 --> 00:45:10,742
-Then who is?
-No one. Everyone. God.

484
00:45:11,463 --> 00:45:12,418
Who knows.

485
00:45:12,503 --> 00:45:16,337
All you have to do is resign yourself
to a few more pokes and pricks.

486
00:45:18,703 --> 00:45:20,022
What if l....

487
00:45:24,103 --> 00:45:26,663
-Evacuate!
