01:10:59,663 --> 01:11:02,302
Open in the name
of the United States government.

732
01:11:02,823 --> 01:11:04,939
Portland, it looks like
the Marines have landed...

733
01:11:05,023 --> 01:11:07,776
-and they don't look too happy.
-This is a joke, right?

734
01:11:07,863 --> 01:11:11,412
-This has got to be a joke.
-l really don't think so, Frannie.

735
01:11:11,823 --> 01:11:14,178
-Hi there, you're on the air.
-Rae, you all right?

736
01:11:14,263 --> 01:11:16,902
To tell you the truth,
it doesn't look good right now.

737
01:11:17,223 --> 01:11:20,659
Several soldiers have just broken in
to the studio. They're fully armed...

738
01:11:20,743 --> 01:11:23,303
and they're dressed
in some kind of protective clothing.

739
01:11:23,383 --> 01:11:25,578
They're wearing respirators
on their faces....

740
01:11:27,143 --> 01:11:28,292
Shut it down!

741
01:11:28,383 --> 01:11:31,420
Bluto, you ever heard of a little number
called freedom of speech?

742
01:11:31,503 --> 01:11:34,142
Bill of Rights? Any of that ring a bell?

743
01:11:34,223 --> 01:11:38,102
Folks, l've been ordered by my uninvited
fascist guests to shut down...

744
01:11:38,183 --> 01:11:40,617
-and l've refused.
-All right, that's enough!

745
01:11:43,183 --> 01:11:47,142
Oh, my God! Daddy, what's happening?

746
01:11:48,823 --> 01:11:50,495
l don't know, honey.

747
01:11:56,103 --> 01:11:59,413
He's closer now! The hard case!

748
01:12:00,623 --> 01:12:03,137
The dark man! He's coming!

749
01:12:37,503 --> 01:12:39,221
Rub-a-dub-dub.

750
01:12:45,543 --> 01:12:47,295
Thanks for the grub.

751
01:12:59,063 --> 01:13:00,382
He's here!

752
01:13:02,343 --> 01:13:05,141
The monster's here! The dark man's here!

753
01:13:54,423 --> 01:13:58,575
Hello there, East Texas. What kept you?

754
01:13:58,823 --> 01:14:00,779
l was lost in the corn.

755
01:14:02,903 --> 01:14:04,780
Then l heard the guitar.

756
01:14:06,063 --> 01:14:07,860
lt sounds so sweet.

757
01:14:09,303 --> 01:14:13,455
l ain't been able to make
a decent F-chord in 20 years...

758
01:14:13,543 --> 01:14:15,261
but thank you kindly.

759
01:14:19,543 --> 01:14:22,057
Who are you? Where is this?

760
01:14:22,743 --> 01:14:27,214
l'm Abagail Freemantle,
and this is Hemingford Home.

761
01:14:30,063 --> 01:14:33,897
Those folks who've got you
won't leave you to live much longer.

762
01:14:34,343 --> 01:14:36,254
You know that, don't you?

763
01:14:36,543 --> 01:14:38,215
l reckon maybe l do.

764
01:14:40,063 --> 01:14:43,021
The beast is loose
in the streets of Bethlehem.

765
01:14:43,823 --> 01:14:47,418
-The rats are in the corn.
-l don't follow you, ma'am.

766
01:14:53,343 --> 01:14:54,617
Ma'am?

767
01:14:58,863 --> 01:15:00,421
Where are you?

768
01:15:01,143 --> 01:15:05,853
Folks round these parts just call me
Mother Abagail, East Texas.

769
01:16:12,783 --> 01:16:15,616
Well, how are we feeling?

770
01:16:17,783 --> 01:16:18,852
Fine.

771
01:16:21,903 --> 01:16:23,336
Always fine.

772
01:16:25,743 --> 01:16:29,258
Just think, all the tests we ran on you...

773
01:16:29,823 --> 01:16:33,293
and we never found
a single immunity vector. Not one.

774
01:16:36,183 --> 01:16:39,175
l'm curious. How would you explain it?

775
01:16:40,423 --> 01:16:42,698
Have you been touched by God?

776
01:16:54,303 --> 01:16:56,737
What have you got behind your back?

777
01:17:05,783 --> 01:17:07,694
-l see.
-Do you?

778
01:17:07,783 --> 01:17:10,138
-l think l do, yeah.
-l wonder.

779
01:17:13,743 --> 01:17:15,938
Where's your buddy Denninger?

780
01:17:17,463 --> 01:17:18,782
He's dead.

781
01:17:20,543 --> 01:17:22,215
They're all dead.

782
01:17:23,943 --> 01:17:27,538
Everyone except for me and thee.

783
01:17:28,343 --> 01:17:30,903
And you're here to take care of me?
ls that it?

784
01:17:30,983 --> 01:17:32,336
Hole in one.

785
01:17:34,943 --> 01:17:35,978
Why?

786
01:17:39,903 --> 01:17:43,293
Because l've decided
a piece of chicken-fried crap like you...

787
01:17:43,383 --> 01:17:47,376
doesn't deserve to live.
Not with so many good men dying.

788
01:17:49,863 --> 01:17:53,060
Those good men caused this mess.

789
01:23:15,463 --> 01:23:19,138
Come down and eat chicken with me,
beautiful. lt's so dark.

790
01:24:01,223 --> 01:24:05,102
You come and see me, Stu.
You and all your friends.

791
01:24:05,183 --> 01:24:08,141
We got to get started. Time's short.

792
01:24:19,583 --> 01:24:21,414
Abagail Freemantle.

793
01:24:23,143 --> 01:24:24,895
Hemingford Home.

794
01:24:46,783 --> 01:24:51,334
You come see me.
You and all your friends.

795
01:25:34,143 --> 01:25:35,178
English

796
01:26:48,303 --> 01:26:49,941
l love you, Daddy.

797
01:26:53,223 --> 01:26:54,815
Frannie loves you.

798
01:27:32,583 --> 01:27:33,652
Fran?

799
01:27:34,103 --> 01:27:36,776
Mr. Goldsmith? Hello?

800
01:27:38,103 --> 01:27:40,776
l'm here, Harold. Come in.

801
01:27:45,743 --> 01:27:47,062
Here.

802
01:27:53,823 --> 01:27:55,302
lt's my father.

803
01:27:56,423 --> 01:27:58,812
l'm going to bury him in his garden.

804
01:27:59,303 --> 01:28:02,375
That's his favorite place.
l think he'll be able to rest there.

805
01:28:02,463 --> 01:28:03,816
l really do.

806
01:28:04,583 --> 01:28:07,734
But l'm so hot and tired.
Could you please help me?

807
01:28:09,503 --> 01:28:10,731
Of course.

808
01:28:47,783 --> 01:28:51,014
Here you go.
lt's a little warm, but it's not too bad.

809
01:28:52,423 --> 01:28:54,732
That's okay. l like warm lemonade.

810
01:28:58,303 --> 01:29:00,214
Harold, it's so strange.

811
01:29:00,503 --> 01:29:03,176
lt doesn't even seem
like the place l grew up in.

812
01:29:03,463 --> 01:29:05,772
lt seems like a different planet.

813
01:29:06,023 --> 01:29:07,854
Yeah, l know what you mean.

814
01:29:09,663 --> 01:29:11,619
l've always hated it here.

815
01:29:11,983 --> 01:29:14,178
All l ever wanted was to escape.

816
01:29:16,223 --> 01:29:19,738
All those guys who used to give me
wedgies in gym class...

817
01:29:19,903 --> 01:29:22,861
all the girls who used to laugh
at the way l walked...

818
01:29:22,943 --> 01:29:24,501
they're all gone.

819
01:29:26,343 --> 01:29:28,095
And l want them back.

820
01:29:30,103 --> 01:29:31,138
Nuts.

821
01:29:38,543 --> 01:29:41,774
For two people from the same town...

822
01:29:42,223 --> 01:29:44,498
two people who know each other...

823
01:29:44,983 --> 01:29:47,656
to both be immune to something this big:

824
01:29:48,463 --> 01:29:51,102
lt's like winning the Megabucks lottery.

825
01:29:52,943 --> 01:29:56,572
-lt has to mean something.
-Well, there's gotta be other people.

826
01:29:56,663 --> 01:30:00,133
We just gotta figure out how to find them,
don't you think?

827
01:30:01,823 --> 01:30:04,212
-We have to go to Stovington.
-Where?

828
01:30:05,383 --> 01:30:07,101
Stovington, Vermont.

829
01:30:07,503 --> 01:30:10,017
There's a government
communicable disease center there.

830
01:30:10,103 --> 01:30:14,415
lf anyone's still alive and trying to find
a cure for the flu, that's where they'd be.

831
01:30:14,503 --> 01:30:17,540
-lmmune cases as well.
-Harold, you're a genius.

832
01:30:18,703 --> 01:30:20,375
That's a great idea.

833
01:30:21,223 --> 01:30:23,942
Of course,
Stovington might be deserted, too.

834
01:30:26,823 --> 01:30:28,415
Roads are jammed.

835
01:30:29,743 --> 01:30:33,372
-Can you ride a motorcycle?
-Yeah. Jess taught me.

836
01:30:34,903 --> 01:30:36,973
Yeah, that's your boyfriend.

837
01:30:37,583 --> 01:30:39,255
Well, not anymore.

838
01:30:42,303 --> 01:30:44,259
Do you think that maybe...

839
01:30:45,423 --> 01:30:49,496
-you know, maybe l could be....
-Harold, we're always gonna be friends.

840
01:30:51,223 --> 01:30:53,259
-Oh, l forgot.
-What?

841
01:30:53,903 --> 01:30:56,133
lt's a surprise. Wait right here.

842
01:30:59,903 --> 01:31:04,579
l found it in the garage
when l was looking for canvas.

843
01:31:06,023 --> 01:31:08,856
lt runs on batteries.
l thought maybe it would cheer me up.

844
01:31:08,943 --> 01:31:10,501
Cheer us both up.

845
01:31:11,183 --> 01:31:13,333
Okay, what do you want to hear?

846
01:33:14,503 --> 01:33:15,731
Hello?

847
01:33:21,823 --> 01:33:23,336
ls anybody here?

848
01:33:44,463 --> 01:33:45,816
Giddyup, boy.

849
01:33:56,663 --> 01:33:57,732
Hello?

850
01:34:01,503 --> 01:34:03,061
ls anybody there?

851
01:34:05,223 --> 01:34:06,895
ls anybody anywhere?

852
01:34:08,063 --> 01:34:09,337
Over here!

853
01:34:10,383 --> 01:34:11,498
Where?

854
01:34:12,903 --> 01:34:14,336
Keep shouting.

855
01:34:14,943 --> 01:34:16,899
l don't believe l need to.

856
01:34:21,623 --> 01:34:25,013
-You're not gonna shoot me, are you?
-Are you dangerous?

857
01:34:25,103 --> 01:34:28,698
l don't know. No, l'm not dangerous.

858
01:34:44,463 --> 01:34:46,374
l can smell your perfume.

859
01:34:51,223 --> 01:34:53,293
l'm glad to see you, too.

860
01:34:54,463 --> 01:34:58,979
Except for the birds, we may be
the only living creatures in this entire city.

861
01:34:59,783 --> 01:35:01,614
Don't you believe it...

862
01:35:02,823 --> 01:35:06,020
'cause there are a lot
of dangerous people out there.

863
01:35:06,103 --> 01:35:09,095
Some of them
are every bit as healthy as we are.

864
01:35:09,183 --> 01:35:11,743
So my gun might not be such a bad idea?

865
01:35:12,783 --> 01:35:13,772
No.

866
01:35:21,703 --> 01:35:23,375
You know something?

867
01:35:28,503 --> 01:35:30,414
l've seen this guy before...

868
01:35:33,143 --> 01:35:36,294
in Times Square,
just before everything went to hell.

869
01:35:37,023 --> 01:35:38,934
Screaming about monsters.

870
01:35:40,023 --> 01:35:42,139
Now he said they were coming.

871
01:35:42,983 --> 01:35:44,382
He was right.

872
01:36:07,463 --> 01:36:12,093
-How rare did you want it?
-Just run it through a warm room.

873
01:36:14,583 --> 01:36:17,655
You know, l was hoping you'd say that.

874
01:36:19,303 --> 01:36:21,817
-Ta-da.
-Thank you.

875
01:36:24,623 --> 01:36:25,903
This one's barely breathing.

876
01:36:25,903 --> 01:36:26,380
This one's barely breathing.

877
01:36:29,943 --> 01:36:31,934
l think l lost my appetite.

878
01:36:32,943 --> 01:36:35,821
-We gotta get out of here.
-l beg your pardon?

879
01:36:35,903 --> 01:36:38,337
l mean, we gotta get out of the city.

880
01:36:38,743 --> 01:36:40,893
l mean, it's not just the odds
of getting shot.

881
01:36:40,983 --> 01:36:44,658
Do you have any idea
what it's going to smell like in two weeks?

882
01:36:44,743 --> 01:36:47,496
Five million people rotting in the July sun.

883
01:36:50,823 --> 01:36:52,142
What is that?

884
01:36:53,903 --> 01:36:55,177
Vitamin C.

885
01:36:58,943 --> 01:37:01,616
Yeah, l'm sorry. lt's none of my business.

886
01:37:02,143 --> 01:37:03,735
Apology accepted.

887
01:37:05,303 --> 01:37:08,898
Mostly because l think you're right.
The Big Apple is baked.

888
01:37:12,143 --> 01:37:14,896
Do you really want me
to go with you, Larry?

889
01:37:15,383 --> 01:37:18,102
Yeah. You betcha.

890
01:37:20,463 --> 01:37:21,532
Good.

891
01:37:22,623 --> 01:37:23,612
When?

892
01:37:30,023 --> 01:37:32,173
l'd say the sooner the better.

893
01:37:33,783 --> 01:37:34,852
Where?

894
01:37:36,663 --> 01:37:39,700
We go west. Towards Nebraska.

895
01:37:40,823 --> 01:37:43,701
There's a town called Hemingford Home.

896
01:37:44,103 --> 01:37:45,934
Nebraska? Why Nebraska?

897
01:37:46,023 --> 01:37:48,583
l've been having these dreams about it.

898
01:37:48,943 --> 01:37:51,935
An old black woman
who calls herself Mother Abagail.

899
01:37:52,583 --> 01:37:55,416
The town's real enough.
l checked the road atlas.

900
01:37:57,063 --> 01:38:00,260
You mean, you're having visions
of an old black woman?

901
01:38:05,463 --> 01:38:07,693
You haven't had dreams like that?

902
01:38:23,423 --> 01:38:26,176
No, l don't dream. l never dream.

903
01:38:28,143 --> 01:38:30,293
Wait. Nadine.

904
01:38:45,543 --> 01:38:47,932
We should get out of this graveyard.

905
01:38:51,943 --> 01:38:54,411
How l love to love Nadine.

906
01:39:08,503 --> 01:39:10,414
Hey, can anybody hear me?

907
01:39:16,943 --> 01:39:18,661
Let me out!

908
01:39:21,303 --> 01:39:22,941
Let me out of here!

909
01:39:37,623 --> 01:39:38,942
You have to.

910
01:39:40,983 --> 01:39:43,099
l'm gonna starve if you don't.

911
01:39:47,183 --> 01:39:49,413
l don't want to starve to death.

912
01:39:50,943 --> 01:39:52,092
Starve.

913
01:40:03,423 --> 01:40:04,776
Just in case.

914
01:40:09,623 --> 01:40:11,261
Emergency supplies.

915
01:40:20,943 --> 01:40:22,615
Anybody!

916
01:41:26,983 --> 01:41:29,178
Bombs away!

917
01:41:41,783 --> 01:41:45,822
Hey, Trash! What'd old lady Semple say
when you torched her pension check?

918
01:41:45,903 --> 01:41:49,134
-Who's there?
-People who play with fire wet the bed.

919
01:41:49,463 --> 01:41:52,660
Gonna stick you in the nuthatch
up in Terre Haute, Trash.

920
01:41:52,743 --> 01:41:56,372
Stick you in the nuthatch and give you
a few thousand shock treatments.

921
01:41:56,463 --> 01:41:57,578
Shut up!

922
01:41:57,663 --> 01:41:59,415
Keep him away from me!

923
01:42:01,743 --> 01:42:04,211
Hey, Trash, why didn't you
burn up the school?

924
01:42:09,223 --> 01:42:10,975
No one's there, Trash.

925
01:42:11,943 --> 01:42:14,662
They're all dead.
They can't hurt you anymore.

926
01:42:14,743 --> 01:42:15,732
Can't hurt me?

927
01:42:15,823 --> 01:42:18,496
-Can't tease you anymore.
-Can't tease me.

928
01:42:18,623 --> 01:42:20,022
Not anymore.

929
01:42:26,303 --> 01:42:27,816
My life for you.

930
01:42:35,703 --> 01:42:36,818
There.

931
01:42:38,583 --> 01:42:40,460
Go, Trashy. Run. Now!

932
01:42:40,743 --> 01:42:42,256
My life for you!

933
01:43:22,623 --> 01:43:24,022
Trashcan Man.

934
01:43:31,743 --> 01:43:32,812
What?

935
01:43:33,143 --> 01:43:34,542
Where are you?

936
01:43:34,903 --> 01:43:36,336
Everywhere.

937
01:43:36,703 --> 01:43:39,661
l will place you high
in my councils, Trash...

938
01:43:40,583 --> 01:43:43,939
and l will set you to burn.

939
01:43:47,103 --> 01:43:49,173
My life for you.

940
01:44:11,183 --> 01:44:12,855
You were right, Lord.

941
01:44:14,103 --> 01:44:16,094
Those prunes did the trick.

942
01:44:16,343 --> 01:44:18,811
But my, don't they taste nasty.

943
01:44:26,583 --> 01:44:29,734
''Once in every generation...

944
01:44:31,103 --> 01:44:34,015
''the plague shall fall among them.''

945
01:44:35,383 --> 01:44:37,613
That's what it says in the Book.

946
01:44:39,503 --> 01:44:43,337
Seems like you maybe
went a little too far this time....

947
01:44:47,103 --> 01:44:48,934
Rats in the corn, Lord.

948
01:44:49,983 --> 01:44:52,258
And the rats are his, ain't they?

949
01:44:53,943 --> 01:44:55,501
Welladay.

950
01:45:08,783 --> 01:45:11,536
l feel them coming in my direction.

951
01:45:13,023 --> 01:45:16,493
Some of them will be going on to him...

952
01:45:17,183 --> 01:45:18,502
won't they?

953
01:45:33,703 --> 01:45:37,059
l hear you, Lord,
and l'm in the way of doing your will.

954
01:45:38,183 --> 01:45:40,219
But l don't much like it.

955
01:45:42,863 --> 01:45:46,458
Hundred and six years old.
Seems a mite long in the tooth...

956
01:45:46,543 --> 01:45:50,855
to be leading the children of lsrael
out of Egypt.

957
01:45:52,223 --> 01:45:54,896
Or the children of America into Colorado.

958
01:46:08,463 --> 01:46:10,931
Doctor said cut out the coffee.

959
01:46:13,423 --> 01:46:15,857
But l just have only one cup a day.

960
01:46:16,543 --> 01:46:18,022
Two cups a day.

961
01:46:20,783 --> 01:46:23,172
Besides, he's dead and l'm alive.

962
01:46:28,543 --> 01:46:31,103
l do what you say, Lord. Don't l always?

963
01:46:31,103 --> 01:46:31,819
l do what you say, Lord. Don't l always?

964
01:46:33,903 --> 01:46:36,019
But even your own son prayed...

965
01:46:36,103 --> 01:46:40,893
that the cup be taken from his lips,
and l'm praying the same thing.

966
01:46:43,223 --> 01:46:45,862
Probably get about the same answer, too.

967
01:47:09,743 --> 01:47:11,859
l got the Lord to protect me!

968
01:47:12,823 --> 01:47:15,178
l ain't scared of the likes of you!

969
01:47:15,543 --> 01:47:17,534
l think you lie, old woman.

970
01:47:19,183 --> 01:47:21,174
Get thee hence, low spirit!

971
01:47:21,583 --> 01:47:23,938
Turn them away if they come, Mother.

972
01:47:24,983 --> 01:47:27,975
Take my advice. Turn them away.

973
01:47:37,583 --> 01:47:39,938
Your blood is in my fists, Mother.

974
01:48:03,983 --> 01:48:08,454
Dear Lord, take this evil vision
from my sight.

975
01:48:27,183 --> 01:48:30,892
lf it's your will to bring them on, God...

976
01:48:32,143 --> 01:48:35,579
better do it before l lose my guts.

977
01:48:36,623 --> 01:48:37,692
Amen.

978
01:49:08,063 --> 01:49:10,623
-Anybody home?
-Help me!

979
01:49:11,783 --> 01:49:13,216
l'm down here!

980
01:49:14,303 --> 01:49:15,861
Please help me!

981
01:49:23,743 --> 01:49:25,973
You sound pretty hungry, rabbit.

982
01:49:47,543 --> 01:49:50,501
Could you let me out of here, mister?
l'll do anything you want.

983
01:49:54,943 --> 01:49:56,296
You poor guy.

984
01:49:57,663 --> 01:49:59,301
You look like kaka.

985
01:50:01,663 --> 01:50:04,700
-Tell me something, Lloyd.
-How do you know my name?

986
01:50:04,783 --> 01:50:06,136
Lucky guess.

987
01:50:07,303 --> 01:50:09,259
How'd you stay alive so long?

988
01:50:09,343 --> 01:50:12,494
l saw it coming down
and l saved up some food. That's how.

989
01:50:17,383 --> 01:50:19,294
Brer Rat. How'd he taste?

990
01:50:27,183 --> 01:50:29,981
Poke should be here, not me.
Everything was Poke's idea.

991
01:50:30,063 --> 01:50:33,658
And you got stuck with nothing
to eat but rat tartare. Bad luck.

992
01:50:33,743 --> 01:50:35,973
Worst damn luck l ever heard of.

993
01:50:36,503 --> 01:50:39,813
But it could just be
that your luck's on the change, Lloyd.

994
01:50:39,903 --> 01:50:41,131
Look here.

995
01:50:50,303 --> 01:50:51,418
My God.

996
01:50:51,703 --> 01:50:54,820
Wait a minute, son.
You ain't seen nothing yet.

997
01:51:01,943 --> 01:51:03,342
Not bad, huh?

998
01:51:06,743 --> 01:51:08,938
l never even introduced myself, did l?

999
01:51:09,023 --> 01:51:12,140
Pleased to meet you, Lloyd.
Hope you guessed my name.

1000
01:51:12,783 --> 01:51:15,661
Nothing. Just a little classical reference.

1001
01:51:16,023 --> 01:51:19,493
Actually, my name's Flagg. Randall Flagg.

1002
01:51:19,943 --> 01:51:21,456
Before l open up this cell door...

1003
01:51:21,543 --> 01:51:24,694
and take you out
for a couple of cheeseburgers and fries...

1004
01:51:25,863 --> 01:51:28,741
l think we ought to have ourselves
a little understanding.

1005
01:51:28,823 --> 01:51:31,462
l'm going to make you my foreman, Lloyd.

1006
01:51:31,783 --> 01:51:34,743
l'm gonna slip the keys
to the kingdom into your hand. l pick you.

1007
01:51:34,743 --> 01:51:35,414
l'm gonna slip the keys
to the kingdom into your hand. l pick you.

1008
01:51:36,623 --> 01:51:39,012
Do you understand that? l pick you.

1009
01:51:41,343 --> 01:51:44,335
Anyone ever done that for you
in your whole miserable life?

1010
01:51:47,943 --> 01:51:49,342
Not even Poke.

1011
01:51:50,703 --> 01:51:53,297
We just, you know, sort of fell together.

1012
01:51:56,463 --> 01:51:58,977
After that, l just kind of got left here.

1013
01:51:59,383 --> 01:52:01,135
''Kind of got left here.''

1014
01:52:02,463 --> 01:52:05,182
That's one way of putting it, l suppose.

1015
01:52:07,703 --> 01:52:12,333
Would you like to get back at those people
who'd leave a man to die in a jail like....

1016
01:52:12,423 --> 01:52:13,856
Well, like him?

1017
01:52:16,343 --> 01:52:19,574
-You bet l would.
-Of course you would.

1018
01:52:19,743 --> 01:52:23,656
But l've got a feeling
you're somebody special. A real find.

1019
01:52:24,063 --> 01:52:25,974
Not exactly a quiz kid...

1020
01:52:27,383 --> 01:52:28,975
but you are the first.

1021
01:52:29,063 --> 01:52:31,452
l'm even going to put you ahead
of Trashcan Man.

1022
01:52:31,543 --> 01:52:34,103
-Who?
-Never mind.

1023
01:52:34,823 --> 01:52:37,018
l need your word
that we're gonna stick together.

1024
01:52:37,103 --> 01:52:39,333
No backstabbing,
no falling asleep on the watch.

1025
01:52:39,423 --> 01:52:42,574
Just you and me, Lloyd.
Win or lose, stand or fall.

1026
01:52:44,103 --> 01:52:46,776
You give me your promise,
l give you the key.

1027
01:52:48,423 --> 01:52:49,697
l promise.

1028
01:53:00,103 --> 01:53:01,980
You're free, Lloyd. Come on out.

1029
01:53:23,583 --> 01:53:24,936
ls that mine?

1030
01:53:40,223 --> 01:53:43,613
-Shall we bite some chow, man?
-Bite some chow, yes, you bet.

1031
01:53:44,463 --> 01:53:47,102
There's a lot to do. We have to work fast.

1032
01:53:47,183 --> 01:53:49,492
-But we can do it, can't we, Lloyd?
-Yes. You bet.

1033
01:53:49,583 --> 01:53:50,982
You and me, soldier. You and me!

1034
01:54:06,303 --> 01:54:08,658
Larry, l can't do it.

1035
01:54:15,423 --> 01:54:16,822
Sure you can.

1036
01:54:17,063 --> 01:54:19,941
-l'll be with you.
-No. You don't understand.

1037
01:54:20,023 --> 01:54:24,574
l can't do it. Dark, confined places.
l can't do it. l'll go crazy.

1038
01:54:26,903 --> 01:54:29,212
-That's great.
-l'm sorry.

1039
01:54:33,423 --> 01:54:35,175
That's just great, Nadine.

1040
01:54:36,023 --> 01:54:38,935
Why you didn't tell me this
before we got 60 or so blocks...

1041
01:54:39,023 --> 01:54:41,253
from the George Washington Bridge
is beyond me.

1042
01:54:41,343 --> 01:54:43,379
Because l thought l could do it.

1043
01:54:46,543 --> 01:54:47,737
Why me?

1044
01:54:50,103 --> 01:54:52,333
And you've had plenty of those,
thank you very much.

1045
01:54:52,423 --> 01:54:54,175
-Give that back.
-No, ma'am.

1046
01:54:54,503 --> 01:54:57,813
l'm not going to stand here
in the middle of five million dead people...

1047
01:54:57,903 --> 01:55:00,019
and watch you commit suicide.

1048
01:55:00,103 --> 01:55:01,058
No!

1049
01:55:04,543 --> 01:55:05,532
Damn you.

1050
01:55:09,863 --> 01:55:12,661
-Where are you going?
-Going to the George Washington Bridge.

1051
01:55:12,743 --> 01:55:14,017
By myself.

1052
01:55:17,143 --> 01:55:21,580
l don't need this prima donna act, missy.
l really don't.

1053
01:55:22,423 --> 01:55:26,621
You have fun getting raped and murdered
back on Seventh Avenue, sweetheart.

1054
01:55:44,863 --> 01:55:47,093
Come on back. This is crazy.

1055
01:55:48,863 --> 01:55:50,455
l'm sorry, okay?

1056
01:55:50,583 --> 01:55:54,417
lf it has to be the bridge, that's fine.
Just don't do it alone.

1057
01:56:02,903 --> 01:56:04,382
The hell with you.

1058
01:56:11,383 --> 01:56:13,055
l'm going in now!

1059
01:57:08,543 --> 01:57:10,374
Don't look at them, stupid.

1060
01:57:34,423 --> 01:57:35,572
Larry.

1061
01:58:47,623 --> 01:58:48,817
Who's there?

1062
01:58:50,823 --> 01:58:52,495
ldentify yourself!

1063
01:58:58,303 --> 01:59:01,295
You better start talking
before l start shooting here!

1064
01:59:10,263 --> 01:59:13,141
Larry, please stop shooting!

1065
01:59:17,863 --> 01:59:20,377
Nadine, you stay where you are,
do you hear me?

1066
01:59:32,503 --> 01:59:34,733
Are you hurt? Did l shoot you?

1067
01:59:34,823 --> 01:59:36,302
No, but l felt the wind....

1068
01:59:36,383 --> 01:59:38,738
One came by so close l felt the wind of it...

1069
01:59:38,823 --> 01:59:43,260
and the tile chips on my face.
l think l cut my face--

1070
01:59:43,623 --> 01:59:45,102
God, l'm so sorry.

1071
01:59:45,183 --> 01:59:46,901
-lt's okay.
-l'm sorry.

1072
01:59:51,343 --> 01:59:54,221
Are you still mad about the pills?

1073
01:59:54,303 --> 01:59:56,976
-No.
-'Cause l won't take the pills, Larry.

1074
01:59:57,343 --> 01:59:59,379
lt's okay.

1075
02:00:25,183 --> 02:00:26,582
Oh, dear God.

1076
02:00:47,023 --> 02:00:48,297
l tell you...

1077
02:00:49,823 --> 02:00:51,939
Jersey never smelled so good.

1078
02:01:25,783 --> 02:01:28,251
l don't think you're singing that just right.

1079
02:01:29,423 --> 02:01:30,572
Take it easy.

1080
02:01:31,743 --> 02:01:33,620
lt's okay, l'm a friend.

1081
02:01:33,943 --> 02:01:35,899
Well, l certainly hope so.

1082
02:01:39,783 --> 02:01:43,332
Just think of it as home defense
while on the road.

1083
02:01:44,023 --> 02:01:46,457
All right, l certainly will.

1084
02:01:47,103 --> 02:01:51,335
-Glen Bateman at your service.
-Stu Redman. Originally from east Texas.

1085
02:01:52,703 --> 02:01:54,898
Kojak, say hello to Stu Redman.

1086
02:01:55,423 --> 02:01:57,414
He's such a miserable dog.

1087
02:01:58,623 --> 02:02:00,500
Don't be too hard on him.

1088
02:02:02,343 --> 02:02:04,652
He's the first dog l've seen in...

1089
02:02:07,863 --> 02:02:09,819
well, since the third week of June.

1090
02:02:09,903 --> 02:02:14,419
Yeah. The superflu took most of the dogs
right along with their idiot masters.

1091
02:02:14,703 --> 02:02:16,056
Most unfair.

1092
02:02:20,103 --> 02:02:23,573
lt might not be a bad idea
to paint with your glasses on.

1093
02:02:23,903 --> 02:02:25,973
Not when you paint like l do.

1094
02:03:01,623 --> 02:03:04,854
l can't do this, Larry. l just.... Not now.

1095
02:03:05,263 --> 02:03:08,539
You can. Sure you can.
You can do anything.

1096
02:03:14,903 --> 02:03:16,700
No, l can't.

1097
02:03:30,543 --> 02:03:31,862
l want you.

1098
02:03:38,743 --> 02:03:40,779
-l know, but--
-Do you want me?

1099
02:03:43,223 --> 02:03:44,497
l know you do.

1100
02:03:46,383 --> 02:03:47,862
So what's the problem?

1101
02:03:49,303 --> 02:03:51,100
l just...

1102
02:03:53,663 --> 02:03:55,096
need more time.

1103
02:03:58,423 --> 02:04:00,015
lt's the dreams?

1104
02:04:02,183 --> 02:04:04,651
-l told you, l don't dream.
-Come on, Nadine.

1105
02:04:09,503 --> 02:04:11,221
l had the same dreams.

1106
02:04:16,023 --> 02:04:19,060
l don't know anything about that. l just....

1107
02:04:23,263 --> 02:04:25,094
l just need more time.

1108
02:04:28,263 --> 02:04:29,537
Yeah, sure.

1109
02:04:31,943 --> 02:04:33,262
Time l got.

1110
02:04:34,943 --> 02:04:36,217
Thank you.

1111
02:05:09,663 --> 02:05:12,894
Folks round these parts
just call me Mother Abagail.

1112
02:05:14,303 --> 02:05:17,898
You'll be coming along to see me,
won't you, Larry?

1113
02:05:19,703 --> 02:05:20,658
Yeah.

1114
02:05:21,983 --> 02:05:23,655
Hemingford Home...

1115
02:05:24,943 --> 02:05:26,342
or Boulder.

1116
02:05:27,343 --> 02:05:29,174
One place or the other.

1117
02:05:36,383 --> 02:05:38,658
So cold.

1118
02:05:39,503 --> 02:05:41,971
No, he's warm. Not you.

1119
02:05:43,743 --> 02:05:45,938
But l'm the one you belong to, Nadine.

1120
02:05:46,503 --> 02:05:48,858
-You are the promised one.
-Why me?

1121
02:05:49,423 --> 02:05:50,776
Who promised?

1122
02:05:53,823 --> 02:05:55,256
That doesn't matter.

1123
02:06:00,943 --> 02:06:03,298
Nadine. My love.

1124
02:06:05,943 --> 02:06:09,413
As long as you hide your mind
from the old woman, you'll be fine.

1125
02:06:11,223 --> 02:06:15,057
-When you come to me, we'll be married.
-Married.

1126
02:06:16,983 --> 02:06:21,374
But l want you to leave
the one you're traveling with. Tonight.

1127
02:06:21,903 --> 02:06:25,054
l can handle Larry. He's just a boy.

1128
02:06:26,823 --> 02:06:28,097
Leave him.

1129
02:07:04,583 --> 02:07:07,495
Larry, by the time you read this,
l'll be gone.

1130
02:07:07,583 --> 02:07:10,859
lf l stay, we'll end up sleeping together,
and l can't have that.

1131
02:07:10,943 --> 02:07:13,855
l have my reasons. Thanks for being there.

1132
02:07:13,943 --> 02:07:16,503
l'll see you again. Much love, Nadine.

1133
02:07:18,543 --> 02:07:20,738
You were right about the dreams.

1134
02:08:20,383 --> 02:08:21,975
Hey, mister, watch out!

1135
02:08:32,783 --> 02:08:36,014
Holy G, mister, but you took a tumble.

1136
02:08:36,103 --> 02:08:38,458
Didn't you just? My laws.

1137
02:08:40,263 --> 02:08:43,858
l'm sorry if l scared you, mister,
but you scared me, too.

1138
02:08:44,463 --> 02:08:47,455
You're the first person l've seen
in just about forever.

1139
02:08:52,303 --> 02:08:54,294
l made that, mister. You like it?

1140
02:08:57,543 --> 02:08:58,737
You bet.

1141
02:08:58,823 --> 02:09:02,736
l got them dummies from the window
of Landon's on the highway to Okie City.

1142
02:09:03,423 --> 02:09:06,972
l thought a few decorations
would cheer up Main Street.

1143
02:09:07,583 --> 02:09:10,097
lt's been awful sad with everyone gone.

1144
02:09:10,943 --> 02:09:12,296
Do you like them?

1145
02:09:15,183 --> 02:09:17,981
Thanks. Decoration is my hobby.

1146
02:09:19,143 --> 02:09:21,782
M-O-O-N. That spells ''hobby.''

1147
02:09:23,943 --> 02:09:27,697
Do you want to go on up the street
to the drugstore and get a Band-Aid?

1148
02:09:28,143 --> 02:09:32,375
We can just take it if we want.
Everyone's gone, so it's not like stealing.

1149
02:09:38,743 --> 02:09:40,859
Sure don't talk much, do you?

1150
02:09:50,823 --> 02:09:53,018
l'm sorry, mister, l can't read.

1151
02:09:56,543 --> 02:09:58,738
Just a few little words is all.

1152
02:09:58,823 --> 02:10:03,180
l went to school. l made it to the
third grade, but then l kind of pooped out.

1153
02:10:03,383 --> 02:10:07,899
l could read some Curious George
when l left, but since then l kind of forgot.

1154
02:10:34,303 --> 02:10:36,612
l'm sorry, mister, l don't get you.

1155
02:10:44,223 --> 02:10:47,579
My daddy always said
l was a little slow on the upchuck.

1156
02:10:48,663 --> 02:10:50,096
That's a joke.

1157
02:10:50,423 --> 02:10:52,891
My daddy was always joking around and....

1158
02:11:00,023 --> 02:11:01,422
l got it, mister!

1159
02:11:03,063 --> 02:11:06,135
You're just like
old Albion Packalotte's hired man.

1160
02:11:06,223 --> 02:11:08,339
Tom Cullen knows what that is.

1161
02:11:08,423 --> 02:11:11,972
M-O-O-N. That spells ''deaf and dumb''!

1162
02:11:25,743 --> 02:11:28,098
When they all coming back, mister?

1163
02:11:29,823 --> 02:11:32,337
l know where they went, laws, yes.

1164
02:11:33,263 --> 02:11:35,493
They up and went to Kansas City.

1165
02:11:37,783 --> 02:11:40,581
They're always talking
about what a dull town this is...

1166
02:11:40,663 --> 02:11:43,257
since the roller rink went bust.

1167
02:11:43,783 --> 02:11:47,139
There's just the drive-in theater
out on Route 61 .

1168
02:11:47,303 --> 02:11:51,660
All they show is them diddly-daddly
pictures and they're all rated ''X.''

1169
02:11:52,183 --> 02:11:54,902
M-O-O-N. That spells ''X.''

1170
02:11:56,383 --> 02:11:58,578
So they all went to Kansas City.

1171
02:12:02,023 --> 02:12:05,140
Except my mama.
She caught a cold and died.

1172
02:12:06,103 --> 02:12:08,663
l put her in the cemetery my own self.

1173
02:12:10,543 --> 02:12:13,819
So she didn't go to Kansas City
with the rest of them.

1174
02:12:14,103 --> 02:12:17,778
She's up in heaven.
She's eating the bread of life with Jesus.

1175
02:12:35,583 --> 02:12:38,620
Mister, if you're going to Kansas City,
can l go with you?

1176
02:12:38,743 --> 02:12:40,301
l ain't never been...

1177
02:12:40,623 --> 02:12:42,773
and l don't want to stay here anymore.

1178
02:12:42,943 --> 02:12:46,299
lt's lonely and it's scary at night.

1179
02:13:09,743 --> 02:13:12,416
Drive a car? Tom Cullen?

1180
02:13:12,823 --> 02:13:14,017
Laws, no.

1181
02:13:16,983 --> 02:13:19,451
l guess you can't drive a car, either.

1182
02:13:31,063 --> 02:13:33,418
l got just the thing for you, ma'am.

1183
02:13:38,583 --> 02:13:41,495
Hey, mister, nice bike. Who's it for?

1184
02:13:48,023 --> 02:13:51,095
You want me to go with you?
To Kansas City?

1185
02:13:54,583 --> 02:13:56,460
To see the old black lady?

1186
02:14:03,983 --> 02:14:07,896
That's right.
She lives in a little house in the corn.

1187
02:14:08,303 --> 02:14:10,612
She plays her guitar on the porch.

1188
02:14:11,423 --> 02:14:15,780
l don't mind going to see her, but
we won't go see the other one, will we?

1189
02:14:16,423 --> 02:14:19,256
The one that turns into a crow
and flies away?

1190
02:14:21,143 --> 02:14:23,782
He wears boots and jeans...

1191
02:14:23,863 --> 02:14:26,696
and a jacket with special buttons on it.

1192
02:14:27,543 --> 02:14:28,942
Face buttons.

1193
02:14:29,663 --> 02:14:33,099
He looks like a man,
but l don't think he's really a man.

1194
02:14:33,343 --> 02:14:35,857
We won't go near him, will we, mister?

1195
02:14:37,063 --> 02:14:39,816
Okay, then. All right, l'm ready.

1196
02:14:40,503 --> 02:14:44,815
Laws, yes. M-O-O-N. That spells ''ready.''

1197
02:14:58,383 --> 02:15:01,500
M-O-O-N. That spells ''Nebraska''!

1198
02:15:27,543 --> 02:15:29,738
Time to get going, Stuart.

1199
02:15:30,503 --> 02:15:32,095
You come see me.

1200
02:15:33,303 --> 02:15:34,656
Who are you?

1201
02:15:36,063 --> 02:15:38,657
-Who are you really?
-Your last hope.

1202
02:15:39,983 --> 02:15:42,451
lf you miss me in Hemingford Home...

1203
02:15:42,863 --> 02:15:46,378
we'll be moving on to Colorado.
l think you know where.

1204
02:15:46,903 --> 02:15:48,734
Boulder. But....

1205
02:15:51,223 --> 02:15:52,861
The rats are his.

1206
02:16:37,303 --> 02:16:41,421
Stay away from her, East Texas.
Stay away or you'll all die.

1207
02:16:50,983 --> 02:16:52,052
The plague!

1208
02:16:56,783 --> 02:17:01,459
You come on along and see me.
You and all your friends.

1209
02:17:06,703 --> 02:17:10,491
Damn dreams are going to drive me crazy
if l don't do something.

1210
02:17:11,943 --> 02:17:15,618
So l'm gonna go to Nebraska.
l gotta find out what this means.

1211
02:17:16,823 --> 02:17:19,178
-You want to come with me?
-Why not?

1212
02:17:19,743 --> 02:17:22,735
Always assuming we can find
a motorcycle with a sidecar.

1213
02:17:22,823 --> 02:17:24,575
l'm not leaving Kojak.

1214
02:17:25,743 --> 02:17:28,018
Well, you don't sound very enthusiastic.

1215
02:17:29,783 --> 02:17:32,058
When l lose sleep, l get cranky.

1216
02:17:34,543 --> 02:17:35,862
Bad dreams?

1217
02:17:38,103 --> 02:17:40,856
The name of the guy in the desert is Flagg.

1218
02:17:41,383 --> 02:17:44,739
And l think he's crucifying anyone
who gets in his way.

1219
02:17:49,623 --> 02:17:51,703
Let's say we go out there to Nebraska
and the old woman's there.

1220
02:17:51,703 --> 02:17:54,012
Let's say we go out there to Nebraska
and the old woman's there.

1221
02:17:54,783 --> 02:17:57,775
''Folks round these parts
call me Mother Abagail.

1222
02:17:58,183 --> 02:18:02,301
''l'm 106 years old
and still make my own bread.''

1223
02:18:03,303 --> 02:18:04,861
Yeah, that's her.

1224
02:18:05,223 --> 02:18:08,181
Let's say she's real. Then what?

1225
02:18:08,263 --> 02:18:10,857
Well, it's obvious
she's some sort of magnet.

1226
02:18:10,943 --> 02:18:14,219
So l suppose we start building
the whole sorry mess up again...

1227
02:18:14,303 --> 02:18:16,373
using her as magnetic north.

1228
02:18:17,623 --> 02:18:19,136
You hear that?

1229
02:18:52,423 --> 02:18:53,981
How you doing?

1230
02:18:55,263 --> 02:18:58,573
l'm Stu Redman.
This here's Glen Bateman.

1231
02:18:59,303 --> 02:19:02,215
And that furry one over there, that's Kojak.

1232
02:19:02,303 --> 02:19:03,452
Fran Goldsmith.

1233
02:19:04,903 --> 02:19:08,418
-We're glad to meet you.
-And we're glad to see you.

1234
02:19:08,863 --> 02:19:11,013
-Aren't we, Harold?
-l don't know.

1235
02:19:11,383 --> 02:19:13,021
Do we assume they're all right...

1236
02:19:13,103 --> 02:19:15,936
just because they remember
how to shake hands?

1237
02:19:16,743 --> 02:19:18,938
No harm intended here, Mr....

1238
02:19:20,743 --> 02:19:22,654
Lauder. Harold Lauder.

1239
02:19:24,383 --> 02:19:28,092
Harold, l don't think l'm ever going to get
these calluses off my fanny.

1240
02:19:30,303 --> 02:19:31,622
Where are you folks headed?

1241
02:19:31,703 --> 02:19:34,661
-Nebraska.
-Stovington, Vermont.

1242
02:19:41,223 --> 02:19:42,656
What? What's wrong?

1243
02:19:43,463 --> 02:19:46,500
Going to Stovington
would be a waste of your time.

1244
02:19:47,183 --> 02:19:49,572
l hardly think you're the best judge of that.

1245
02:19:49,663 --> 02:19:52,814
He was there. And he knows.
They tried to kill him.

1246
02:19:53,303 --> 02:19:55,294
-Really?
-Yeah.

1247
02:19:57,063 --> 02:19:58,212
Look...

1248
02:20:00,383 --> 02:20:03,341
Glen and l were about ready
to head to Nebraska.

1249
02:20:05,823 --> 02:20:10,260
We've been having the same dream--

1250
02:20:10,343 --> 02:20:12,140
The dreams are an aberration.

1251
02:20:14,783 --> 02:20:18,856
Maybe, but we're all headed
in the same direction.

1252
02:20:18,943 --> 02:20:20,501
-Why don't we go together?
-Okay.

1253
02:20:20,583 --> 02:20:22,062
-No.
-Harold.

1254
02:20:24,303 --> 02:20:26,180
l don't like the looks of them.

1255
02:20:27,343 --> 02:20:29,174
This one in particular.

1256
02:20:34,983 --> 02:20:38,259
Can l talk to you for a second? Come on.

1257
02:20:45,383 --> 02:20:49,058
l'm gonna talk straight to you now, okay?
Between you and me.

1258
02:20:50,623 --> 02:20:53,012
l do not want to cut in on you here.

1259
02:20:53,343 --> 02:20:56,255
That's the last thing in the world
that l want.

1260
02:20:58,383 --> 02:21:00,738
Relax. The last thing in the world.

1261
02:21:18,863 --> 02:21:20,182
Here you go.

1262
02:21:23,103 --> 02:21:24,172
-Okay.
-No, thanks.

1263
02:21:24,543 --> 02:21:25,771
You sure?

1264
02:21:33,903 --> 02:21:35,621
Not bad. Cold.

1265
02:21:35,983 --> 02:21:37,462
Enjoy it.

1266
02:21:37,543 --> 02:21:41,616
l have a feeling there's gonna be
a shortage of cold beer this summer.

1267
02:21:43,143 --> 02:21:46,340
-l still want to check Stovington.
-Harold, why?

1268
02:21:47,703 --> 02:21:49,375
Let's just say l'm from Missouri.

1269
02:21:49,463 --> 02:21:52,899
And l don't always take the word
of people l just met as gospel.

1270
02:21:55,063 --> 02:21:56,337
All right.

1271
02:21:57,943 --> 02:22:01,219
But there isn't anything there
you're gonna wanna see.

1272
02:22:42,303 --> 02:22:43,975
Still from Missouri?

1273
02:23:10,783 --> 02:23:15,334
You was right. l never should have
eaten all them apples. Laws, no.

1274
02:23:21,943 --> 02:23:23,501
Where you going?

1275
02:23:27,823 --> 02:23:32,374
Don't worry, l ain't going nowhere.
My legs feel all funny.

1276
02:24:28,183 --> 02:24:31,220
My God. Are you real?

1277
02:24:42,863 --> 02:24:44,979
lf you're real, say something.

1278
02:24:57,183 --> 02:24:58,855
Are you a deaf-mute?

1279
02:25:04,063 --> 02:25:07,260
Somebody finally shows up
in this crappy town...

1280
02:25:07,343 --> 02:25:09,698
and it turns out to be a deaf-mute.

1281
02:25:13,863 --> 02:25:17,492
Well, hi. My name's Julie Lawry.

1282
02:25:19,263 --> 02:25:21,254
You can't tell me yours, can you?

1283
02:25:23,223 --> 02:25:24,417
Poor you.

1284
02:25:29,383 --> 02:25:31,374
Does baby have a sad tummy?

1285
02:25:42,303 --> 02:25:43,895
Ain't he a moose?

1286
02:25:50,623 --> 02:25:55,333
''l'm Nick Andros. My friend is Tom Cullen.
He's mildly retarded.''

1287
02:26:00,583 --> 02:26:03,143
A retard and a deaf-mute. Just my luck.

1288
02:26:03,903 --> 02:26:04,972
What?

1289
02:26:15,143 --> 02:26:17,941
Do all deaf-mutes have such big guns?

1290
02:26:21,303 --> 02:26:22,782
They do?

1291
02:26:47,583 --> 02:26:48,777
Peekaboo.

1292
02:26:50,703 --> 02:26:52,182
What?

1293
02:26:53,703 --> 02:26:56,263
No. Hold me.

1294
02:26:56,903 --> 02:26:58,495
You gotta hold me.

1295
02:26:59,863 --> 02:27:01,455
l've been lonely.

1296
02:27:25,503 --> 02:27:27,334
No, no. What's that?

1297
02:27:28,823 --> 02:27:30,461
He's just a retard.

1298
02:27:30,543 --> 02:27:33,455
He doesn't feel things
the way that you and l do.

1299
02:27:33,543 --> 02:27:34,862
He can wait.

1300
02:27:47,263 --> 02:27:48,332
What?

1301
02:27:51,383 --> 02:27:52,577
Get out.

1302
02:27:53,383 --> 02:27:54,782
Stupid dummy.

1303
02:28:01,943 --> 02:28:04,503
lt was those apples. Laws, yes.

1304
02:28:05,103 --> 02:28:09,142
l don't want it. No, sir. Say, who's that?

1305
02:28:10,983 --> 02:28:12,860
How you doing, cutie-pie?

1306
02:28:13,943 --> 02:28:16,457
l heard you weren't feeling too good.

1307
02:28:17,143 --> 02:28:18,974
Your name's Tom, right?

1308
02:28:20,343 --> 02:28:21,617
Tom Cullen.

1309
02:28:22,103 --> 02:28:26,016
-M-O-O-N. That spells ''Tom Cullen.''
-Yes.

1310
02:28:27,063 --> 02:28:29,213
l don't want medicine, mister.

1311
02:28:29,303 --> 02:28:32,534
That's right. You know what l know
about that stuff? That stuff's poison.

1312
02:28:32,623 --> 02:28:37,333
No, sir. Tom Cullen doesn't drink poison.
Daddy said, ''Don't you ever.''

1313
02:28:37,423 --> 02:28:40,779
Daddy said if it killed the rats
in the barn, it'd kill me, too.

1314
02:28:40,863 --> 02:28:44,094
Please don't make me
drink it, mister. Please.

1315
02:28:46,463 --> 02:28:49,614
His daddy said, ''Don't do it.''
Don't make him do it.

1316
02:28:57,023 --> 02:28:59,856
l got Mighty Mouse here with pink lips...

1317
02:28:59,943 --> 02:29:03,060
and a big old moose over there
crying just like a baby.

1318
02:29:07,583 --> 02:29:09,255
Dummy freak bastard!

1319
02:29:19,663 --> 02:29:22,177
Yeah, that's right. You wouldn't dare.

1320
02:29:25,823 --> 02:29:28,383
Please. Don't fight.

1321
02:29:28,543 --> 02:29:31,615
l feel better now. l can go on, see?

1322
02:29:48,943 --> 02:29:51,218
Fine, l'll read your crappy note.

1323
02:29:57,943 --> 02:30:01,413
lt was just a joke, dummy. lt was a joke.

1324
02:30:02,943 --> 02:30:06,094
Joke, stupid. lt was a joke!

1325
02:30:10,023 --> 02:30:12,583
l'm gonna get you.
You and your stupid freak friend.

1326
02:30:12,663 --> 02:30:14,813
l'm gonna get both of you guys!

1327
02:30:40,383 --> 02:30:43,295
Sorry, mister. l cry like a baby.

1328
02:30:43,823 --> 02:30:46,462
But she scared me. Laws, yes.

1329
02:30:52,303 --> 02:30:53,531
You, too?

1330
02:31:09,103 --> 02:31:10,377
Laws, yes!

1331
02:31:10,663 --> 02:31:13,575
Let's get out of here
before she comes back.

1332
02:31:19,263 --> 02:31:23,097
She's shooting at us!
Come on, mister, we gotta get out of here!

1333
02:31:26,663 --> 02:31:29,223
Come on! l want to see you run!

1334
02:31:37,463 --> 02:31:41,251
lf l ever see any of you two
in my face again, l'll kill you!

1335
02:32:38,783 --> 02:32:41,013
Hot. Laws, yes.

1336
02:32:50,423 --> 02:32:51,742
What is it?

1337
02:32:57,063 --> 02:33:01,853
Mister, we gotta go. We gotta hide!
What if.... That could be her!

1338
02:33:07,063 --> 02:33:09,816
She's back there.
Laws, yes, Tom knows that...

1339
02:33:11,343 --> 02:33:13,538
but what if that one's like her?

1340
02:33:23,183 --> 02:33:26,459
He might be like us? Nice, like us?

1341
02:33:59,503 --> 02:34:02,734
Holy crow! Am l glad to see you fellows.

1342
02:34:05,263 --> 02:34:07,333
You boys headed to Nebraska?

1343
02:34:09,423 --> 02:34:13,336
My friend can't talk.
He's deaf and dumb. But he's smart.

1344
02:34:16,503 --> 02:34:19,336
l bet he is. He got that look, don't he?

1345
02:34:20,223 --> 02:34:21,975
Name's Ralph Brentner.

1346
02:34:23,543 --> 02:34:24,976
l'm Tom Cullen.

1347
02:34:25,183 --> 02:34:27,981
M-O-O-N. That spells ''Tom Cullen.''

1348
02:34:28,943 --> 02:34:33,698
l don't know his name 'cause l can't
read it. Sure wish l did, though. Laws, yes.

1349
02:34:44,303 --> 02:34:47,056
Your friend's name here is Nick Andros.

1350
02:34:47,983 --> 02:34:50,099
M-O-O-N. l guess that spells ''Nick.''

1351
02:34:50,983 --> 02:34:53,178
Nick Andros. How you doing?

1352
02:34:56,903 --> 02:34:58,780
Why don't you boys climb on in?

1353
02:34:59,263 --> 02:35:01,731
We got some miles to turn before dark.

1354
02:36:21,183 --> 02:36:22,502
Thank God!

1355
02:36:22,863 --> 02:36:26,572
l'm so happy.
We're so happy to see someone else.

1356
02:36:26,903 --> 02:36:27,972
Right, Joe?

1357
02:36:28,823 --> 02:36:31,895
-l'm so pleased to meet you.
-Same here, believe me.

1358
02:36:33,463 --> 02:36:35,055
How you doing, son?

1359
02:36:35,863 --> 02:36:36,898
Joe!

1360
02:36:37,623 --> 02:36:39,022
Put that away.

1361
02:36:39,103 --> 02:36:42,140
Nice kid. Has he had his rabies shots yet?

1362
02:36:42,423 --> 02:36:46,336
l'm sorry. He's been traumatized.

1363
02:36:47,063 --> 02:36:48,337
Haven't we all?

1364
02:36:49,423 --> 02:36:50,776
l suppose so.

1365
02:36:54,623 --> 02:36:56,102
l'm Lucy Swann.

1366
02:37:00,463 --> 02:37:01,737
The boy...

1367
02:37:02,583 --> 02:37:05,302
l found him in a supermarket in lowa City.

1368
02:37:05,503 --> 02:37:08,654
He was just wandering around
and eating sweet stuff.

1369
02:37:09,543 --> 02:37:11,693
Back then, he was almost feral.

1370
02:37:12,103 --> 02:37:14,219
You took him with you anyway.

1371
02:37:15,023 --> 02:37:16,854
He would have died on his own.

1372
02:37:22,183 --> 02:37:26,256
So what do you think happened here?
l mean, you think it was lightning, or....

1373
02:37:26,783 --> 02:37:28,614
lt started around dusk.

1374
02:37:28,783 --> 02:37:32,219
lt was a whole series of explosions
on the west side of town...

1375
02:37:32,303 --> 02:37:33,895
where the tank farms are.

1376
02:37:34,263 --> 02:37:36,982
Then, later that night, there was a wind...

1377
02:37:37,343 --> 02:37:39,982
and by morning,
the rest of the city was gone.

1378
02:37:40,063 --> 02:37:41,382
l'd say it was set.

1379
02:37:43,543 --> 02:37:46,899
You think somebody deliberately burned
Des Moines to the ground?

1380
02:37:47,583 --> 02:37:48,618
Yes.

1381
02:37:53,263 --> 02:37:56,892
Who'd want to burn a whole city
to the ground, for God's sakes?

1382
02:38:05,383 --> 02:38:07,294
Cibola.

1383
02:38:11,463 --> 02:38:13,658
My life for you.

1384
02:38:16,903 --> 02:38:21,613
l will set you high in my councils,
and l will set you to burn.

1385
02:38:25,383 --> 02:38:26,611
Cibola.

1386
02:38:27,383 --> 02:38:31,058
The city, as promised.

1387
02:38:48,863 --> 02:38:52,538
Thank you, Lord.
l didn't drop it on the floor.

1388
02:38:55,983 --> 02:38:58,577
Now, Lord, l ain't picked the corn yet.

1389
02:38:59,343 --> 02:39:03,302
Maybe some of those men you're sending
will help me out.

1390
02:39:25,143 --> 02:39:28,021
Thank you, my Lord,
for bringing them to me.

1391
02:39:30,743 --> 02:39:32,176
Hello, Mother.

1392
02:39:33,663 --> 02:39:36,735
Ralph Brentner.
l'm so pleased to meet you.

1393
02:39:40,143 --> 02:39:43,613
We never made a single wrong turn.
Nick here knew just how to come.

1394
02:39:47,703 --> 02:39:49,022
Hello, Nick.

1395
02:39:51,143 --> 02:39:53,054
Glad to see you.

1396
02:39:54,183 --> 02:39:55,411
God bless.

1397
02:39:58,383 --> 02:40:00,817
You've done it, Nick.
You've brought them through.

1398
02:40:01,423 --> 02:40:03,539
You're the first of many.

1399
02:40:04,783 --> 02:40:06,375
You're all welcome here.

1400
02:40:06,863 --> 02:40:10,697
Our time is very short,
but we'll break bread together...

1401
02:40:10,783 --> 02:40:13,251
and have some fellowship,
one with the other.

1402
02:40:13,343 --> 02:40:15,811
-Granny lady?
-What, honey?

1403
02:40:16,223 --> 02:40:18,612
Are you the oldest lady in the world?

1404
02:40:18,983 --> 02:40:21,019
Gina. That's not polite.

1405
02:40:21,943 --> 02:40:25,538
Mayhap so, sweetheart. Mayhap so.

1406
02:40:39,863 --> 02:40:41,854
That was a dilly of a meal, ma'am.

1407
02:40:42,423 --> 02:40:43,856
lt wasn't bad.

1408
02:40:44,223 --> 02:40:45,895
Birds was a little tough.

1409
02:40:46,383 --> 02:40:48,977
''But it's a hell of a lot tougher
where there's none''...

1410
02:40:49,063 --> 02:40:50,815
my own mama used to say.

1411
02:40:51,703 --> 02:40:55,821
Now l've made up a cot for the little one
in the back room.

1412
02:40:56,823 --> 02:40:59,940
-The woman, what's her name, Ralph?
-Susan. Susan Stern.

1413
02:41:01,183 --> 02:41:05,176
A goodish name.
She can bunk with the tot.

1414
02:41:08,263 --> 02:41:12,461
How did you know to come to me
in the first place?

1415
02:41:15,943 --> 02:41:17,899
We dreamed of you, Mother.

1416
02:41:18,543 --> 02:41:20,499
Of you and the other fellow.

1417
02:41:23,183 --> 02:41:24,696
The other fellow.

1418
02:41:27,943 --> 02:41:30,138
Come on, you. Time for bed.

1419
02:41:33,423 --> 02:41:35,300
God bless the child.

1420
02:41:37,023 --> 02:41:40,299
God bless the child that's got her own.

1421
02:41:43,463 --> 02:41:44,862
l was told...

1422
02:41:45,303 --> 02:41:48,534
that we're gonna be
like a snowball rolling downhill...

1423
02:41:48,743 --> 02:41:51,382
picking up other people as we head west.

1424
02:41:52,103 --> 02:41:54,412
Told? Told by who, Mother?

1425
02:41:54,823 --> 02:41:56,142
Told by God.

1426
02:41:56,623 --> 02:42:01,333
l tried not to hear what God had to tell me
but you can see all the good it done.

1427
02:42:04,983 --> 02:42:07,099
You been drafted, too, Nick.

1428
02:42:07,463 --> 02:42:09,897
God has his finger on your heart.

1429
02:42:10,583 --> 02:42:13,620
And He's got more fingers than one.

1430
02:42:14,503 --> 02:42:18,018
There's dark work ahead
for his chosen ones.

1431
02:42:19,503 --> 02:42:21,061
Dark and bloody.

1432
02:42:34,463 --> 02:42:35,691
Ma'am...

1433
02:42:36,623 --> 02:42:39,740
what if this dark man
we've been dreaming about isn't real?

1434
02:42:40,183 --> 02:42:43,937
What if he's, what do you call it,
a bogeyman?

1435
02:42:44,983 --> 02:42:47,497
You dreamed of me. Am l the bogeyman?

1436
02:42:49,463 --> 02:42:50,612
No, ma'am.

1437
02:42:50,703 --> 02:42:52,421
He's real all right...

1438
02:42:53,903 --> 02:42:57,134
and it's our lot to deal with him.

1439
02:42:57,223 --> 02:42:59,532
God don't explain his will...

1440
02:42:59,783 --> 02:43:02,058
to the likes of Abby Freemantle.

1441
02:43:11,863 --> 02:43:12,898
Well?

1442
02:43:15,503 --> 02:43:16,822
Nick says....

1443
02:43:20,743 --> 02:43:22,973
He says he don't believe in God.

1444
02:43:28,903 --> 02:43:32,179
God bless you, Nick, but it don't matter.

1445
02:43:33,143 --> 02:43:35,532
He believes in you.

1446
02:44:07,103 --> 02:44:08,331
l'm fine.

1447
02:44:10,023 --> 02:44:12,332
Just thinking some long thoughts.

1448
02:44:16,503 --> 02:44:19,415
My daddy owned all this once.

1449
02:44:20,543 --> 02:44:22,340
As far as your eye can see.

1450
02:44:29,823 --> 02:44:31,814
And my brothers lost it...

1451
02:44:32,143 --> 02:44:34,657
a piece at a time, after he was gone.

1452
02:44:35,743 --> 02:44:37,062
Finally...

1453
02:44:38,143 --> 02:44:40,782
the only thing left was the home place.

1454
02:44:42,743 --> 02:44:44,973
What l said to myself was:

1455
02:44:45,983 --> 02:44:49,293
''Don't worry, Ab. They can have the rest.

1456
02:44:49,383 --> 02:44:51,897
''l'll hang on to the home place...

1457
02:44:54,023 --> 02:44:55,581
''come what may.''

1458
02:44:58,743 --> 02:45:00,176
And now look at this.

1459
02:45:01,743 --> 02:45:05,452
Look at my things,
sitting in the back of that damn truck.

1460
02:45:07,303 --> 02:45:10,454
And look at me, getting moved on...

1461
02:45:11,423 --> 02:45:14,620
like a vagrant turned out of a boxcar
by railroad dick.

1462
02:45:18,223 --> 02:45:19,895
ls that what God is?

1463
02:45:21,423 --> 02:45:24,813
A big old railroad dick,
who'd like to whop you upside your head...

1464
02:45:24,903 --> 02:45:28,452
if you don't step as lively
as he wants you to step?

1465
02:45:30,783 --> 02:45:32,216
Oh, Jesus!

1466
02:45:42,463 --> 02:45:43,976
You guys coming?

1467
02:45:44,343 --> 02:45:45,981
Daylight's wasting.

1468
02:45:54,663 --> 02:45:56,062
Come on, Nick...

1469
02:45:58,823 --> 02:46:00,415
Ralph's waiting.

1470
02:46:19,823 --> 02:46:21,097
All right.

1471
02:46:22,423 --> 02:46:23,697
Let's go.

1472
02:46:33,063 --> 02:46:34,815
Boulder, here we come!

1473
02:47:58,343 --> 02:47:59,537
Cibola !

1474
02:48:06,503 --> 02:48:09,256
My life for you.

1475
02:48:19,863 --> 02:48:22,252
Wonderful city of gold!

1476
02:48:22,823 --> 02:48:25,895
Seven in one. My life for you.

1477
02:48:40,703 --> 02:48:42,102
Anybody here?

1478
02:49:11,463 --> 02:49:14,614
-What are we gonna do with him?
-Let him sleep. Flagg wants him.

1479
02:49:14,703 --> 02:49:16,534
Where is Flagg, anyway?

1480
02:49:17,863 --> 02:49:20,058
You that anxious to see him, Barry?

1481
02:49:21,023 --> 02:49:23,378
l just thought....

1482
02:49:24,383 --> 02:49:27,216
Flagg will be around.
He's been waiting for this guy.

1483
02:49:27,463 --> 02:49:29,533
This guy's something special.

1484
02:49:30,223 --> 02:49:31,781
My life for you.

1485
02:49:41,783 --> 02:49:45,981
Thank You, Lord,
for bringing us across the prairie...

1486
02:49:46,183 --> 02:49:49,334
and to this place
where the mountains begin.

1487
02:49:50,343 --> 02:49:54,097
Please take care of us
in the days and weeks to come...

1488
02:49:55,623 --> 02:49:59,411
and help us to love one another
and do your will...

1489
02:49:59,943 --> 02:50:03,219
however hard it may
sometimes seem to us.

1490
02:50:08,983 --> 02:50:11,338
Tom ! Tommy, come look!

1491
02:50:13,463 --> 02:50:16,819
-What is it, Gina?
-A parade. Come on up and look.

1492
02:50:20,943 --> 02:50:22,217
Gosh, it is!

1493
02:50:31,143 --> 02:50:33,577
M-O-O-N. That spells ''parade.''

1494
02:50:48,023 --> 02:50:50,173
Help us to be true, dear Lord.

1495
02:50:51,503 --> 02:50:53,812
Help us to stand.

1496
02:52:25,303 --> 02:52:26,292
English

